* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)

  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Ibdb2ebccfd782ed5e01b7f0c4bfb6294c89232c6

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

(1 comment)

The main use case this breaks for me is being able to use "run_tests.sh -d -V" and using pdb to debug unit tests.  Is that kind of thing possible in our tox env?'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-09-22 19:11:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yes you can do that with ostestr which is what tox is calling. There is a --pdb flag which will skip testr, subunit (which is what interferes with pdb), and test discovery, and execute what you specify on the param with testtools.run directly. So for example you can do:

tox -epy27 -- --pdb cinder.tests.unit.test_gpfs

(you can also specify per class or method too)'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-09-22 19:20:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-09-22 19:21:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'm wary of removing all of this in one go.  The other day we had a conversation on IRC about how "you can now only generate sample config w/ tox" has left some people hanging, and this seems likely to cause similar issues.

Do we really know that "run_tests.sh -N" is not a valuable tool to anyone at this point?  What's the replacement for that for workflows where you want to run tests against dependencies that are packaged or installed by something other than tox?  Those are likely to exist in environments where people are packaging Cinder for distribution rather than installing things via pip.

Statements like "It is now better to just run tox." really only apply to the obvious developer use cases, but I suspect there are other cases too...  we should really make sure before just tossing this out.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-10-05 20:31:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Thanks Eric. This is exactly why I wanted to throw this out there to be able to start capturing feedback if there was any reason to keep it around.

Do you think this should be scoped back to just start removing some functionality from run_tests (pep8, coverage, ?) and add a warning that it may go away completely? Then if anyone is using it and finds a reason they can't switch to tox we can find out before just taking it away."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-10-05 20:48:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Hi,

As the package maintainer for all of OpenStack in Debian, I'm voting no to this one. Note because I'm against removing run_tests.sh per say (I'm in fact *for* it), but because I tried running "ostestr" and also manually running testr using: PYTHONPATH=`pwd` PYTHON=python2.7 testr-python2 run --subunit | subunit2pyunit, but then I get loads of unit test errors with the errror: RuntimeError: No 'cinder.database.migration_backend' driver found, looking for 'sqlalchemy'. This way, out of 6880 unit tests, I get 6763 failures! So something is definitively going wrong. Please find a way for distros *before* pushing for such a change. I'm of course open to any other commands which you see fit, though it is my view that just running what is in tox.ini should "just work (tm)".

So, yes, by all means, let's remove run_tests.sh. But please don't just impose tox, which doesn't work for distributions. Make it possible to just run the command which is documented in tox.ini directly by distros.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-10-05 20:54:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hey Thomas, the correct way to run the tests are from the root directory just call "tox" or "tox -e py27" to run the tests.

Is this used somehow in the distros? I assumed this would only be useful for development. I wasn't aware of a packaging need for this.'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2015-10-05 20:57:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

It may be reasonable to get rid of it, since I guess people who need to run native tests have alternatives like running "python -m subunit.run" or similar.

Removing parts of it (-V in particular) is probably not great because it would make the "multiple ways to run tests" issues worse, when one of them doesn't work for lots of cases.

We could also do something like map most of the parameters to just run tox commands and leave -N as-is... -V for a standard tox run, -p for "tox -e pep8", -c for "tox -e cover" etc.  This would cut out most of the complexity of the script.

I'm not too opposed to removing it, but it lands more in "why do this?" territory than "this is a clear win" to me, especially considering the above option.'}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2015-10-05 21:02:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

tox --sitepackages should work with system installed python packages'}, {'account_id': 10635, 'date': '2015-10-05 22:24:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

check microsoft-iscsi-ci'}, {'account_id': 13915, 'date': '2015-10-06 06:39:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

run cinder-quobyteci-dsvm-volume'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-10-07 11:17:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

Hi, Sean McGinnis.

No, we can't use tox in distributions, that is not the way we do to run unit tests, as it may download things from internet (which is not possible during build).

Though I think I have found out the solution, by reading what's in the run_tests.sh, which is:

python setup.py egg_info && testr init && testr run --subunit

So I'm transforming my -1 into a +1"}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-10-07 13:37:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Thanks Thomas. Just so I understand - you're saying unit tests are run during the distribution packaging process?"}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-10-08 11:47:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Sean, yes they are. And that is truth for each and every packages for OpenStack in Debian. Unit tests are always run, and the package build process fails if unit tests are failing. This ensure that we have a correct set of (build-)dependencies with the correct version, and that software behaves as expected.

Once a full release of OpenStack is packaged and ready (like, just right now...), I do run tempest to do functional testing. Tempest is also available as a Debian package for doing this. For the moment, I do run only tempest included functional testing, though it is one of my todo list items to also run each and every individual set of functional tests included in all projects. During this process, I may also discover issues with configuration files, as what is included (or generated in) each project is in use for these Tempest tests. This is how I discover issues with the Cinder config file generation.

Hoping that these insights help.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-10-08 13:35:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks Thomas!'}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-10-08 20:23:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Would like some reference of this being the preferred way from the community. I might've missed the cross-project communication on this."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:30:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-10-10 13:21:55.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Accomplished one I intended of stirring the pot and seeing what folks had to say. Pretty mixed, but I think there are some reasons to still keep run_tests around. At least some of the arguments are captured here if it's ever questioned again."}]

commit_message:
Remove run_tests.sh wrapper

The run_tests.sh mechanism for performing operations
is no longer the preferred approach. It is now better
to just run tox.

To get rid of confusion by having two different ways
to run unit tests, flake8 checks, etc., it's probably
better to just remove the run_tests.sh script completely
and direct folks to use tox instead. This way we are all
consistent and there is less concern that changes will
be made to one and not the other.

Change-Id: I17af7ed0e5c1d5649f5ba4418b09fa301245d6fc

commit_message:
Adding pagination to snapshots and backups lists

Snapshot and backups pagination was recently implemented in the Cinder
backend. This patch is implementing a pagination for the snapshots and
backups on the client side in the same way that volume pagination works
using limit, marker and sort parameters.

Partial-Implements: blueprint extend-limit-implementations
Change-Id: Ie3660854407a947f7470b4dc0911704c0a31c1b4

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-20 18:08:44.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Fix format inconsistencies in the way swift server returns error responses

The error response generation in all the servers inside swift is pretty
much inconsistent. They don't respect the accept header of the request.
In some parts, the accept header isn't passed to the backend server at all.
Some parts, even when the backend server responds with a proper format
response such as JSON, and sets the content-type also accordingly, the proxy
server overwrites it with the standard text/html content-type. Some parts,
we always hard code and return text/plain error response, irrespective of the
content type asked. This patch is a attempt to fix all those incosistencies.
This is a WIP. Need feedback/comments about the direction I'm heading.

Change-Id: Id49342705a72abd6bf810b77838a00ebdf501559
"}]
commit_message:
WIP: Fix format inconsistencies in the way swift server returns error responses

The error response generation in all the servers inside swift is pretty
much inconsistent. They don't respect the accept header of the request.
In some parts, the accept header isn't passed to the backend server at all.
Some parts, even when the backend server responds with a proper format
response such as JSON, and sets the content-type also accordingly, the proxy
server overwrites it with the standard text/html content-type. Some parts,
we always hard code and return text/plain error response, irrespective of the
content type asked. This patch is a attempt to fix all those incosistencies.
This is a WIP. Need feedback/comments about the direction I'm heading.

Change-Id: Id49342705a72abd6bf810b77838a00ebdf501559

commit_message:
Fixing cluster creation without auto_security_group

If auto_security_group is disabled, but one or more
security groups is provided, cluster can't be created
and fails with yaml RepresenterError exception.

Change-Id: I294237c788c2d14d77f12e1a8d7e0dd60a6638bb
Closes-bug: #1504093

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).
The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).
This patch fix the issue in the module magnum/tests/unit/api/.

Change-Id: I947346f36212ad518b68ac31ef83cf594e125153
Partial-Bug: #1259292

commit_message:
Make sure keystone is up before trying to use it

On some systems, keystone may not be up and running yet when the scripts
try to call it. To fix this race, make the scripts wait for keystone.

Change-Id: I6151cbfa6d16ff50a6d7eb0799e2818751dc175b

commit_message:
Create a routing table manager

The routing table manager maps address scope ids to routing tables.
It uses the rt_tables file specific to each namespace to maintain the
mapping so that id can simply be used as the table name when running
iproute2 commands.  This will be useful when debugging.

Change-Id: Ic3332b0f9fbba2b2a6ae2e0d495145d0a1ae1be0

commit_message:
Modularizing Neutron playbooks for master

Adding modularization for neutron setup for master.

- Core Plugin can be selected by name, and new ones added to the
  'plugins_neutron' data structure
- Agents are enabled/disabled through 'services_neutron' dict
  in roles/os_neutron/defaults/main.yml
- Upstart tasks for agentss are run based on individual enabled status
- Agent service names propagate to appropiate handler

Note: The current implementation can be further optimized when
      we move to ansible-v2. The neutron_upstart_init.yml can be
      reduced to a single task that loops on the neutron_services
      dict.

Implements: blueprint modularize-neutron-liberty

Change-Id: I9f6a5edbec79d46e2a69cb60366a8af5a4d6a7a0
Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>
(cherry picked from commit ac4f224195251bceaed1fb83bde45b311571f99b)

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).
The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).
This patch fix the issue in the module magnum/tests/functional/.

Change-Id: Ic5151d6052780180179189cf47cc41f9215e2af5
Partial-Bug: #1259292

commit_message:
API Quick Start Translations

Setup Japanese API Quick Start for building and checking.
Markup German not anymore as draft.

Do not publish content anymore on docs.openstack.org, our
jobs are going to use publishlang-api to publish on
developer.openstack.org instead.

Change-Id: I67d777a6c271fc8dc1ebe3e75b81a09e7c5c3efb

Publishing is now only done on developer.openstack.org and not anymore
on docs.openstack.org:
* Remove api-site-tox-doc-publishdocs
* Create new job openstack-api-ref-publish-lang to publish translated
  documents to developer.o.o.
* Remove api-site-tox-doc-publishlang job (published translated
  documents to docs.o.o). For this, we need to replace the
  openstack-doc-translation template with individual jobs.

Change-Id: Id9d9c378c29e5601fe994b46ede19ddae61cfb53
'}]
commit_message:
Rework api-site publishing

Publishing is now only done on developer.openstack.org and not anymore
on docs.openstack.org:
* Remove api-site-tox-doc-publishdocs
* Create new job openstack-api-ref-publish-lang to publish translated
  documents to developer.o.o.
* Remove api-site-tox-doc-publishlang job (published translated
  documents to docs.o.o). For this, we need to replace the
  openstack-doc-translation template with individual jobs.

Change-Id: Id9d9c378c29e5601fe994b46ede19ddae61cfb53

commit_message:
Remove old files used for enabling murano in Devstack

As we are using new plugin model for enabling murano
in devstack, the files in the path "/contrib/devstack/
extras.d/" and "/contrib/devstack/lib/" had not been
using now. So they can be removed which might be
confusing the user.

Implements blueprint outdated-devstack-murano-files
Change-Id: I12ee36743f98fdd50d42bd8c2f5d3b9d132bd4c8

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-10 08:00:16.000000000', 'message': 'Remove quotes from subshell call in bash script

Always no quotes for $() statement.

We don't need quotes to hold blanks in result:
 # i=$(echo 1 2 3)
 # echo $i
 1 2 3
 #

These quotes can make something wrong in some case:
 # i=$(echo '!')
 #
 # i="$(echo '!')"
 -bash: !: event not found
 #

No real problem for current code, only to use a better code style.

Change-Id: I8249b148b27af577f6b2ca990311f64f339606f7
Signed-off-by: Zhao Lei <zhaolei@cn.fujitsu.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Remove quotes from subshell call in bash script

Always no quotes for $() statement.

We don't need quotes to hold blanks in result:
 # i=$(echo 1 2 3)
 # echo $i
 1 2 3
 #

These quotes can make something wrong in some case:
 # i=$(echo '!')
 #
 # i="$(echo '!')"
 -bash: !: event not found
 #

No real problem for current code, only to use a better code style.

Change-Id: I8249b148b27af577f6b2ca990311f64f339606f7
Signed-off-by: Zhao Lei <zhaolei@cn.fujitsu.com>

commit_message:
Don't run gate-python-glanceclient-python34 on stable/juno

python-glanceclient didn't support python 3.4 in Juno so the job fails
hard, let's exclude it from stable/juno.

This is blocking Ie6547d1a5501f2d2ec74d3ec4808c26a48ffc7fb.

Change-Id: I7d84cc0d35021bc70fb9745d9300ffdc1ce63bfb

commit_message:
zuul/layout: run puppet integration on horizon module

Horizon is now installed & tested by puppet-openstcak-integration.
This patch aims to run the jobs for puppet-horizon as non-voting, beside
other modules.

Change-Id: I2c8df603dd5bbe9893ff0c80cfb8716d098f1748

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-01 21:05:29.000000000', 'message': 'Baymodel create should allow no network_driver specified

When a kubernetes baymodel is created, the current API validation
only allows an explicit setting of "flannel" for the network-driver
attribute. This validation needs to be changed to allow a user to
create a kubernetes baymodel without explicitly specifying a
network driver. (The same goes for docker swarm and mesos baymodels,
that is, baymodel create should allow the user not to specify
a network-driver, but this is the current behavior).

When no network-driver is selected for baymodel create for a
given COE, Magnum should choose the default network driver for that
COE. Note that this change set only handles the validation for
the case where no network-driver is selected; mapping this to
the COE-dependent default network driver will be done in other
commits (e.g. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224367/ for swarm).

Note that no new unit test cases were added for this patch since
test_create_baymodel_with_network_driver and
test_create_baymodel_with_no_network_driver test cases in
test_baymodel.py should cover this change.

Change-Id: I0735f79354bc9fdb141e7a559517268e8ab648ec
Closes-Bug: 1501077

commit_message:
Baymodel create should allow no network_driver specified

When a kubernetes baymodel is created, the current API validation
only allows an explicit setting of "flannel" for the network-driver
attribute. This validation needs to be changed to allow a user to
create a kubernetes baymodel without explicitly specifying a
network driver. (The same goes for docker swarm and mesos baymodels,
that is, baymodel create should allow the user not to specify
a network-driver, but this is the current behavior).

When no network-driver is selected for baymodel create for a
given COE, Magnum should choose the default network driver for that
COE. Note that this change set only handles the validation for
the case where no network-driver is selected; mapping this to
the COE-dependent default network driver will be done in other
commits (e.g. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224367/ for swarm).

Note that no new unit test cases were added for this patch since
test_create_baymodel_with_network_driver and
test_create_baymodel_with_no_network_driver test cases in
test_baymodel.py should cover this change.

Change-Id: I0735f79354bc9fdb141e7a559517268e8ab648ec
Closes-Bug: 1501077

commit_message:
py3: Replace urllib imports with six.moves.urllib

The urllib, urllib2 and urlparse modules of Python 2 were reorganized
into a new urllib namespace on Python 3. Replace urllib, urllib2 and
urlparse imports with six.moves.urllib to make the modified code
compatible with Python 2 and Python 3.

The initial patch was generated by the urllib operation of the sixer
tool on: bin/* swift/ test/.

Change-Id: I61a8c7fb7972eabc7da8dad3b3d34bceee5c5d93

commit_message:
Change message of log_deprecated decorator

It is unclear what is deprecated in current message.

For example, methods `wait_for`, `wait_is_ready` and `wait_for_delete` were
deprecated in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/232438 . Deprecation
messages are equal, so logs are equal too:

    Deprecated, use wait_for_status instead. (deprecated in Rally v0.1.2)

This patch adds deprecated method's name, so it is easier to determine what
method produces deprecation log message.

Also, this patch adds ability to print warning message once, which can be
helpful for deprecated methods used in scenarios.

Change-Id: Id86e984986ecb61e7b92cc61882382179fc8a74b

commit_message:
Extract random nested level from Cinder scenario

Extract random nested level from create_nested_snapshots_and_attach_volume.
Scenario fail with a big probability. The problem is that in every iteration
scenario creates different number of atomic actions which is not supported
by Rally project. This leads to not proper behavior of Rally reporting.
E.g. it will show that failure rate of some atomic actions is
N% (where N > 0) but overall failure rate is 0%.

Change-Id: Ib1fddfb9fba1cbe64acb8acce3b86cb292bb9b20
Closes-Bug: #1487628

commit_message:
use keystoneauth instead of keystoneclient

we should start using keystoneauth for plugin and sesssion bits
instead of keystoneclient, since that's the direction going
forward.

Change-Id: I04234f830f1880b23ade8ce3f8bca4fe6ac3bc25

[{'created': '2015-10-02 08:29:23.000000000', 'message': 'Port scheduler host manager to Python 3

* Rewrite ReadOnlyDict using collections.Mapping: collections.Mapping
  has no method to modify the dictionary and is available on Python 2
  and Python 3. Add also a __repr__() method to ease debug. Remove
  ReadOnlyDict.update() method: a read-only dictionary must not be
  modifiable.
* test_host_manager.py: sort dictionaries using a key function to
  have a reliable order for the list of dictionaries. On Python 3,
  the hash function is now randomized.
* tox.ini. add cinder/tests/unit/scheduler/ tests to Python 3.4

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I34d98d6a75fef907251719f0d46b025d8e8b2b65
'}]
commit_message:
Port scheduler host manager to Python 3

* Rewrite ReadOnlyDict using collections.Mapping: collections.Mapping
  has no method to modify the dictionary and is available on Python 2
  and Python 3. Add also a __repr__() method to ease debug. Remove
  ReadOnlyDict.update() method: a read-only dictionary must not be
  modifiable.
* test_host_manager.py: sort dictionaries using a key function to
  have a reliable order for the list of dictionaries. On Python 3,
  the hash function is now randomized.
* tox.ini. add cinder/tests/unit/scheduler/ tests to Python 3.4

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I34d98d6a75fef907251719f0d46b025d8e8b2b65

Specifying list_limit in [identity] section has no effect on the returned
user list size.

[{'created': '2015-07-01 17:19:11.000000000', 'message': "Introduce a simple state machine module

States are used in an ad-hoc fashion all over Nova codebase. It's high
time we added some code that will let us define and abstract basic
operations with state changes.

This commit adds 2 classes that will be used to define the state graph,
and a simple way to step through the state graph akin to a state
machine, which will then validate that we are in fact not doing

class State is holds a namespace and a name of the state, and the list
of states that we could go from it. Both the name and the object itself
index the same state and can be used interchangeably within a
state-space. Each Space instance references 0 or more other spaces
within the same namespace as it's next_states thus creating a directed
graph.

class States represent a very simple state machine. When instantiated
with an initial state and a current one, it provides a step() primitive,
which allows transitioning to an allowed next state in the graph. For
ease of use, it also provides a set() primitive for setting the state
machine into a known state.

Change-Id: Ic3c9dbd4af8fe92499d84d43ca3e48783f3a59de

"}, {'created': '2015-07-03 22:13:33.000000000', 'message': 'Introduce a simple state machine module

States are used in an ad-hoc fashion all over Nova codebase. It's high
time we added some code that will let us define and abstract basic
operations with state changes.

This commit adds 2 classes that will be used to define the state graph,
and a simple way to step through the state graph. For this we use the
"automaton" library, that is already in uses by several other OpenStack
projects for similar purposes.

Class State is holds a state-space and a name of the state, and a list
of states that we could go from it. Each State instance references 0
or more other states within the same state-space as it's next_states
attribute thus creating a directed graph.

Class FSM represents a state machine, and is a slightly customized
version of the automaton FiniteMachine class that when given a
state-space, builds a graph of all known states and it's transitions,
and also exposes a step() method that will either progress the machine
to a new state or raise an error if the transition is not valid for the
given state-space.

Related-blueprint: migration-fix-resource-tracking
Change-Id: Ic3c9dbd4af8fe92499d84d43ca3e48783f3a59de

commit_message:
Introduce a simple state machine module

States are used in an ad-hoc fashion all over Nova codebase. It's high
time we added some code that will let us define and abstract basic
operations with state changes.

This commit adds 2 classes that will be used to define the state graph,
and a simple way to step through the state graph. For this we use the
"automaton" library, that is already in uses by several other OpenStack
projects for similar purposes.

Class State is holds a state-space and a name of the state, and a list
of states that we could go from it. Each State instance references 0
or more other states within the same state-space as it's next_states
attribute thus creating a directed graph.

Class FSM represents a state machine, and is a slightly customized
version of the automaton FiniteMachine class that when given a
state-space, builds a graph of all known states and it's transitions,
and also exposes a step() method that will either progress the machine
to a new state or raise an error if the transition is not valid for the
given state-space.

Related-blueprint: migration-fix-resource-tracking
Change-Id: Ic3c9dbd4af8fe92499d84d43ca3e48783f3a59de

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I555bdeba198b1b468884ffce3702f5b06247d573

commit_message:
Remove openstack_deploy from teardown.sh deletion list

This patch prevents teardown.sh script from deleting
/etc/openstack_deploy in order to let the deployer decide whether to
delete it or not.

Change-Id: I8de55c6fce79bd9301d995c565cfb4e0a38b253a
Closes-Bug: #1504561
(cherry picked from commit 6f21ceb86559f9d2c0f0bc765b1602e79cbd10f6)

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I8b884ef477bbc031da6bd3955ed308679e0380f6

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I4a2926f2a80eab35a654400b1f451b5b8ee3e869

Make bootstrap-ansible script compatible with RHEL

This patch enables the bootstrap-ansible.sh script to also work on RHEL
and other "yum" based Linux distributions.

Change-Id: I3e28f4f4f09e7387c97afc219899bba1927215e8

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: If983dae0260ea2a1df49b4bdb0ada3c5223012c9

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I11607fcb400fab9b6096ca8af191c2f2f4b6eca9

commit_message:
py34: cleanup

* Tests were skipped due to a mox3 bug. The bug has now been fixed
  and there's a new release of mox3. Unskip it.
* Remove the tool run-py3-tests.sh which isn't needed anymore.

blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I304d87e4313148c10a2465bf92ae932f525bb4ce

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Ib909ebb74ece9d72d3b8c8ab5b7750cf3f1af09b

* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I4b72eef7fd4d4ee7b226a5014b7d180506161f69

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I42fb3d11d65e261bd5fb0ccb757a68965699a693

commit_message:
Only get host data for floating ips on DVR routers

First, we are only interested in setting the host attribute when
the router is a DVR router.  Second, we don't need to query all of
the ports on the host, we just need to query the ports that are
referenced by the set of floating ips that we already have.

(cherry picked from commit 3c5cb9d050d09424c3f8eb3cd1ecd6876f50a6fe)

Closes-bug: #1496974
Change-Id: If611de14b2ab77d2eb9ce8c5b307ea6dd4403fe1

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I7b5af3ea6b21009a505a8b6c49086d339eaa43e5

commit_message:
Change os-url to os-auth-url on call to OSC

A change was made to the openstackclient that allows the --os-url
switch to be used only when --os-token is used. As we removed the
use of --os-token a while back, we need to switch to using
--os-auth-url instead of --os-url.

Change-Id: Ia769cd4e07e845746adb10d5c25d5095623a8a32
Closes-bug: bug/1504303

commit_message:
Reduce size of CoreOS ramdisk

By disabling pip cache, we're able to reduce the size of generated
docker image by 10%. The resulting ramdisk size goes from 229MB to
218MB.

It is possible to decrease the size even further by combining all the
RUN instructions into one but it doesn't provide a substantial gain and
it harms readability.

Change-Id: Ie23636fe709ab7c1bcf4d6c51299c173a5b642ac

commit_message:
Use puppet to configure ironic-inspector

This removes the ironic-inspector element from the
undercloud install, and instead uses the puppet module
to setup the ironic-inspector service.

Depends-On: I9b2917a2c3f6afe75dc295c81d09f7a12856007f
Change-Id: Ic3eca27515721000ed1c9d19a2427276e6b1af68

commit_message:
Switch to use `region_id` for endpoint APIs

`region` field is deprected in favor of `region_id` since keystone v3.2,
please refer to keystone v3 API spec [1].

[1] http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/keystone-specs/api/v3/identity-api-v3.html#endpoints-v3-endpoints

Change-Id: I5d88449e3b0ac53093eba2d8157a620616d9769c

[{'created': '2015-09-30 04:28:56.000000000', 'message': 'Remove confusing parameter description in heat API

  At first, Current documentation is correct
  in programatically.
  But it makes confusing for user about "resource_name".
  This patch intends to remove confusing documentation.

  Of course, keep, or add notice for same parameter,
  are another option.

  #Detail#

  Event listing in heat uses common filtering engine.
  And its query parameter is common which includes
  "resouce_name"
  and some REST API uses resource_name in URL.

  its code is here
  heat/api/openstack/v1/events.py

Change-Id: Ie7030fb6ba15b6ee7e66fd3f39c03bed1f736782
Closes-Bug: #1500621
'}]
commit_message:
Remove confusing parameter description in heat API

  At first, Current documentation is correct
  in programatically.
  But it makes confusing for user about "resource_name".
  This patch intends to remove confusing documentation.

  Of course, keep, or add notice for same parameter,
  are another option.

  #Detail#

  Event listing in heat uses common filtering engine.
  And its query parameter is common which includes
  "resouce_name"
  and some REST API uses resource_name in URL.

  its code is here
  heat/api/openstack/v1/events.py

Change-Id: Ie7030fb6ba15b6ee7e66fd3f39c03bed1f736782
Closes-Bug: #1500621

[{'created': '2015-10-09 22:55:56.000000000', 'message': "Document unsearchable_fields configuration option

Although RBAC prevents protected fields appearing in search results, it
cannot prevent searching those fields directly. A long term solution is
a separate admin-only index but for now we add a resource plugin option
'unsearchable_fields' which is comma separated and accepts wildcards as
elasticsearch's mapping_template allows. These fields are turned into
index: no, include_in_all: False mapping templates. The value of this
(plus anything coded into a plugin) is also used to redact fields in
_source for non-administrative users.

This patch provides the documentation update for:
 - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/233225/

(cherry picked from commit 0f1518e3d636045350df4a5e8dd8807530691359)
"}]
commit_message:
Document unsearchable_fields configuration option

Although RBAC prevents protected fields appearing in search results, it
cannot prevent searching those fields directly. A long term solution is
a separate admin-only index but for now we add a resource plugin option
'unsearchable_fields' which is comma separated and accepts wildcards as
elasticsearch's mapping_template allows. These fields are turned into
index: no, include_in_all: False mapping templates. The value of this
(plus anything coded into a plugin) is also used to redact fields in
_source for non-administrative users.

This patch provides the documentation update for:
 - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/233225/

Change-Id: I94f47515391cf81d72a6a0d09e7a554259a1f8fb
Partial-Bug: #1504399
(cherry picked from commit 0f1518e3d636045350df4a5e8dd8807530691359)

I will remove, but be aware that this kind of back and forth is what companies in OASIS expressed to me as why they don't want to work in OpenStack.  We are not a "core" service like Nova or keystone with dozens of developers, at this stage of our lifecycle we need function that works. Hi Matt. I appreciate you addressing my comments earlier.

And I understand your point and the fact that we are handling (or try to handle) reviews pretty much similar to other projects. I'm not sure if review guidelines can vary by project, but if I'm asked to adjust I can do that :). 

Having said that, I like even the tiniest nits that pick in our reviews because it's all toward cleaner, and more understandable code. Plus, it makes us be more diligent with out coding (and sometimes learn a thing or two as it has been the case for me). And if we don't fix these issues before they go in, we would hardly find the time and opportunity later to do so with the growing codebase and workload.

Just my humble opinion :)"}, {'account_id': 6456, 'date': '2015-10-09 23:00:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-09 23:01:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: -Verified

commit_message:
Added checking for invalid or malformed command line parameters

The parse_parameters function needed additional logic to recognize and
reject bad parameters.  Primarily, this fix assures that each
parameter is a valid assignment of the form 'a=b'.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1503515

Change-Id: I79d55359743f9c06fb006292fc61dae273e97eb8

commit_message:
Modify admin_api policy rule

Magnum API's magnum_service:get_all is enforced by admin_api.
Modifying the rule to use context_is_admin. Also changing the to_dict()
call to include change in roles.

Change-Id: I44dda27857945dfd3ad43fa28ea458ce2966388c
Closes-Bug: #1503402

commit_message:
WIP Functional test needs to have two types of user

At present, we are continuing the functional test with one user only,
which happens to be 'admin'. This defeats any test based on role, or
similar policy enforcement.

This was a carry over from when the test was originally written in
b3c3cb9c331e9ee54832326420ebe7ac4bf2e080 over 2 years ago.

We shouldn't have to stop the instances in order to delete them, that

commit_message:
Remove _stop_instances hack in test_volume_boot_pattern

This was a carry over from when the test was originally written in
b3c3cb9c331e9ee54832326420ebe7ac4bf2e080 over 2 years ago.

We shouldn't have to stop the instances in order to delete them, that
would be a bug in nova if the delete failed for some reason because the
instances are still active.

Change-Id: I20b7c2e4c2b110933244ba65a1ccdbf246266946

commit_message:
Fix the condition of nova cert tests

This changes nova certification tests to run only if nova_cert is enabled.

Change-Id: I41e53401418c68758830d3009516b5017531b03b
Closes-Bug: 1488420

This is pure config settings and can be easily handled in local.conf.'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-02-03 19:10:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Fair enough, these can all be set with the local.conf file. Maybe I misunderstood the purpose of the cinder_backends scripts, the others seem to do this same kind of thing by being a helper to simplify the configuration.

My main goal for adding this is to reduce confusion in configuring DevStack to use our Cinder backend. Right now you need to set something like: CINDER_ENABLED_BACKENDS=pure:puredriver-1 in local.conf, where the "pure" prefix means nothing (but some string is required), and the "puredriver-1" string is pretty much arbitrary, but *must* match up with default_volume_type and volume_backend_name settings for cinder to make the tests pass due to the default behavior of the cinder setup script.

With this change that CINDER_ENABLED_BACKENDS=pure:puredriver-1 takes advantage of the smarts built in to the cinder setup script by choosing to use the "pure" cinder_backend script to setup the correct backend names and volume types so you don't need to make sure all the strings match up.

So, with all that in mind, is simplification of config files something preferred or to remove complexity from the setup scripts and keep more in the config files? I can understand the benefits of either direction...'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-10-09 21:47:07.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add a pure cinder_backend to configure PureISCSIDriver

This will allow for setting a few configuration options in local.conf
and remove having to specify so much in explicit Cinder and Nova conf 
sections.

Implements: blueprint pure-cinder-backend
Change-Id: I02d7d0cb75b9dc3e3295be1a5c785af20316f8e2

commit_message:
Remove root owned ipsec.secrets for ensure_configs

Since LibreSwan requires that ipsec.secrets be owned by root, the
strategy of rewriting the ipsec.secrets file by writing to a temp file
and renaming causes a permission error and fails to overwrite. This
patch removes the target ipsec.secrets file before running the
ensure_configs operations.

This patch also changes the logging in the _process_running check from
error to info. It isn't an error and will occur under normal
operations.

Change-Id: Id00613e7ca11310e4f65b557b136e02d9783d0d4

commit_message:
Do not log an error when deleting a linuxbridge does not exist

When you're racing to teardown and relying on RPC, it should not be
considered an error that a bridge does not exist when you're trying to
delete it anyway. This is better served as debug level information.

For context, this shows up over 1000 times in successful
gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-linuxbridge job runs in a week so it's
probably safe to say it's not contributing to test failures.

Closes-Bug: #1501779

Change-Id: I8e9b27e010d033291497f4e660a97bbae92e75b1
(cherry picked from commit a9dc48f5a4616a505824c3e8520c3dce7436f1b1)

A number of configuration errors prevent the successful creation of code
coverage. This corrects the .coveragerc source/omit setup and the tox
package name generation.

commit_message:
Workaround potential failure to shutdown services

Kill them twice to make sure they're good'n'dead. There is a supposed
fix to oslo-incubator code, but we're working around that here in the
meantime with this change.

This returned in Liberty.

Change-Id: I02a7af995dc7de857c4efcf2cef2f95d357c007a
Related-Bug: #1446583

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-25 06:50:21.000000000', 'message': "Use dictionary literal for dictionary creation

Dictionary creation could be rewritten as a dictionary literal.
for example:

expect_namespace = {}
expect_namespace['namespace'] = 'MyNamespace'
expect_namespace['protected'] = True

could be rewritten as

expect_namespace = {
    'namespace': 'MyNamespace',
    'protected': True
}

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I76265c26861916ed01cadb62e9201aa871183566
"}]

commit_message:
Clean up the basic install instructions

Moved everything not related to the delorean repos out of
repositories.txt so that it can be reused for the update page.

Changed refrences to discovery image to ironic-python-agent image.

Fixed missing DIB_YUM_REPO_CONF export. The ironic-python-agent
ramdisk can not build without this.

Change-Id: I054dedd7749eac093b24ac1e3e4f4e47fdb41fe2

commit_message:
Remove usage of WritableLogger from oslo_log

With Eventlet 0.17.2, we can directly pass the logger instance. This
allows us to deprecate/remove the WritableLogger class from oslo.log.

Closes-Bug: #1440773
Change-Id: I3985b30b499a1e676d39c2a6cd3a31ac13c0ab47

commit_message:
Document unsearchable_fields configuration option

Although RBAC prevents protected fields appearing in search results, it
cannot prevent searching those fields directly. A long term solution is
a separate admin-only index but for now we add a resource plugin option
'unsearchable_fields' which is comma separated and accepts wildcards as
elasticsearch's mapping_template allows. These fields are turned into
index: no, include_in_all: False mapping templates. The value of this
(plus anything coded into a plugin) is also used to redact fields in
_source for non-administrative users.

This patch provides the documentation update for:
 - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/233225/

Change-Id: I94f47515391cf81d72a6a0d09e7a554259a1f8fb
Partial-Bug: #1504399

I would prefer that we not auto-complete the information, and instead raise an error when we have a protocol version conflict, which is a patch I'm working on in

https://review.openstack.org/215768"}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-09-30 00:38:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Sean :
The patch https://review.openstack.org/215768 will operate on the fact that the IP Version and Source/Destination IP Address version are in conflict.

However, consider the fact that user does not provide IP Version argument, but provides Source and IP Address as IPv6 format.
Then in that case, IP Version wil be set to default(4) and the addresses will be in IPv6.

That was what this patch is targetting to fix.
If the IP Version is not provided and Source/Destination version is , then it can be auto-completed to show proper information'}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-09-30 02:02:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I don't believe that the API should try to "fix" things up for a user. The API requires the ip_version attribute. It tries to be helpful by providing a default. 

Frankly there is a bigger discussion that we could have about if having an ip_version attribute is even worth it, when we have src and destination and can detect what type of IP version it is. 

However, being explicit is better than implicit, so in this case I don't think we should try and fix it for the user. We should just return an error.

Obviously, if we were to change the API and drop ip_version and instead autodetect, this behavior would be correct. But in the absence of that, this is how I feel.'}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-09-30 03:30:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Sean,
Ok, I agree with your point from pythons perspective that explicit is better than implicit.
But the way ip_version operates is still not correct, in both your bug as well as mine.
And with respect to fixing the value, I guess that is what neutron-fwaas is also doing, fixing the default value of 4 instead of making the correct decision.

I am trying to find out a better approach to solve this problem from the client side, instead of the code which conflicts with your bug.

However I am still not able to understand the importance of ip_version field in the whole fwaas implementation.'}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-09-30 03:52:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Sean,
Also, the bug https://review.openstack.org/#/c/215768/ may not be able to handle the case where Source IP Address is IPv4 and Destination IP Address is IPv6.
That is possible in firewall rules.'}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-09-30 03:54:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Sean :Although, I think the above is a bug, and should be fixed nontheless. Then maybe your fix will also validate the ip_version.'}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-09-30 15:34:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Can you expand upon the statement that it is possible to have IPv4 src and IPv6 as dest or vice versa in a firewall rule? Unless I am mistaken, the only time there is an IPv4 src that is then sent to IPv6 dest (or vice versa) is during protocol translation, and if I am not mistaken, protocol translation means creating new packets, with some of the contents preserved. The original src or dst that is IPv4 is not preserved in this case.'}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-10-01 01:14:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

You are right.
After NAT, the packet information changes, and the changes need to be rolled back so that the original Packet can be used.

However, Firewall rule , right now, allows creation of a rule which has IPv4 Source and IPv6 Destination.

The rule creation is successful and visible in the DB, but it puts Firewall in Error condition.
Its better not to allow the creation of such rules itself , either from Horizon or from python-neutronclient.'}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-10-01 07:03:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

Need more discussion on this bug , and the behaviour of ip_version itself'}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-10-01 15:15:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> However, Firewall rule , right now, allows creation of a rule which has IPv4 Source and IPv6 Destination.

Right - which is why I wrote https://review.openstack.org/215768'}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-10-02 02:06:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Sean,
Lets discuss the further outcome for the IP Version on Bug#1497066, as discussed in yesterday meeting.
However I would like to proceed with the discussion once your code has been merged because that is a valid use case. :)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-09 06:10:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Update IP Version based on Source/Destination IP Address

IP Version in firewall rules was earlier updated only when --ip-version
was explicitly passed to the firewall-rule-create CLI.Now,based on the version
of the IP Address of the passed Source/Destination, the IP Version field in
firewall rules are automatically updated.Default value is used if no address
is passed to the CLI. Source Address is given higher priority.
This reduces the chance of user providing IPv6 address in source/destination
and the CLI showing IP Version as 4.

Closes Bug:#1497066

Change-Id: Iba708db9bd3afb7485ecaf173a67d4acd60b713d

commit_message:
Improve documentation for Liberty release

The documentation cross linking from the devstack rst to the
individual plugins is missing due to the devstack rst living
in a different directory. We just need to provide a bit better
linking from devstack as well as a bit more info on each plugin
for where to place to the configuration options for each plugin.

There is also opportunity to make the documentation between
plugins more consistent and provide release note information.

Change-Id: Ib64eeda8a9f5b59777135537de60f049952a4660
Closes-Bug: #1500647
(cherry picked from commit 7079f81421ae94e7e26816ad6097d9753062ad35)

commit_message:
disable port_security for VRRP ports

For tenant networks port_security makes sense, but for the VRRP router
case it can get in the way. This change disables it for Akanda managed
ports for now.

Change-Id: I0fb9fd5253ad0538a35b25d8806323f83cfc48e4
Closes-bug: #1482389

commit_message:
Don't index admin-only fields

Although RBAC prevents protected fields appearing in search results, it
cannot prevent searching those fields directly. A long term solution is
a separate admin-only index but for now we add a resource plugin option
'unsearchable_fields' which is comma separated and accepts wildcards as
elasticsearch's mapping_template allows. These fields are turned into
index: no, include_in_all: False mapping templates. The value of this
(plus anything coded into a plugin) is also used to redact fields in
_source for non-administrative users.

Documentation update in a separate patch.

Change-Id: Ie5bd3fa55ff43fd1a6f52478866261734bd7a051
Closes-Bug: #1504399
(cherry picked from commit fb61e54f00c5f0a750235d3b2fc737d46d50aab5)

commit_message:
Cleaned up remaining incorrect usage for LOG.exception

- callers should not explicitly pass exceptions into LOG.exception
  because it's already implicitly included in the message by stdlib
  logging module.
- callers should not call to LOG.exception when there is no exception to
  log about (known to fail in Python 3.x < 3.5).

Change-Id: I58e7e01ed152028ad43bb3ada87d719caa2ab08d
Related-Bug: #1504053

commit_message:
Explicitly install tox

When testing OVN with Kuryr using a setup which only installs Neutron,
keystone, mysql and OVN, the devstack run fails because tox is not
installed. It was being pulled in when installing tempest. Since
networking-ovn uses genconfig to generate a config file, make sure
we install this ourselves.

With this run, my devstack with Kuryr works now.

Sure. It you take a look at:
https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/master/oslo_messaging/tests/functional/utils.py#L60
you can see that all fixture classes initialize wrapped object using global cfg.CONF

But some of our functional tests use different ConfigOpts object:
https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/master/oslo_messaging/tests/functional/test_functional.py#L28

So in this case your TestCase prepare new configuration for test but oslo.messaging transport is configured using global cfg.CONF.

I don't know how it is working now. But it looks like a bug and current pika driver implementation is sensitive to it because it uses conf.prog and conf.project attributes for queue name constructing"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-06 20:28:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

[{'created': '2015-10-09 19:08:07.000000000', 'message': "Don't index admin-only fields

Although RBAC prevents protected fields appearing in search results, it
cannot prevent searching those fields directly. A long term solution is
a separate admin-only index but for now we add a resource plugin option
'unsearchable_fields' which is comma separated and accepts wildcards as
elasticsearch's mapping_template allows. These fields are turned into
index: no, include_in_all: False mapping templates. The value of this
(plus anything coded into a plugin) is also used to redact fields in
_source for non-administrative users.

Documentation update in a separate patch.

Change-Id: Ie5bd3fa55ff43fd1a6f52478866261734bd7a051
Closes-Bug: #1504399
"}]
commit_message:
Don't index admin-only fields

Although RBAC prevents protected fields appearing in search results, it
cannot prevent searching those fields directly. A long term solution is
a separate admin-only index but for now we add a resource plugin option
'unsearchable_fields' which is comma separated and accepts wildcards as
elasticsearch's mapping_template allows. These fields are turned into
index: no, include_in_all: False mapping templates. The value of this
(plus anything coded into a plugin) is also used to redact fields in
_source for non-administrative users.

Documentation update in a separate patch.

Change-Id: Ie5bd3fa55ff43fd1a6f52478866261734bd7a051
Closes-Bug: #1504399

Add Ceilometer configuration ttl setting for expirer

The Ceilometer expirer tool depends on the TTL configuration option to
determine the time-to-live of samples in the Ceilometer database.

great work! i echo the earlier comments.

a few additional things as well...

Overall, I'd like to see this not based on RHEL atomic. That way folks without a Red Hat subscription can try it out. CentOS atomic might work, but ideally I think it should just be a normal OS with docker installed.

I think it will be important to get the interface right at the container backend level...so if you want to use atomic or just docker compose...what would the templates look like? what parts would be reusable, etc? I think we should try and address this point prior to landing a patch this big to avoid a big refactoring later on.

It might also be useful to try and break this up into smaller pieces. Would it be possible to deploy a puppet based controller and a container based compute? That would make iterating on this work a little easier I think. Especially since the controller here just uses nova network doesn't it? If we could use the puppet based controller then we could continue to push on the container work while neutron gets containerized.

The README here also doesnt mention anything about how to setup your docker registry and build the images, etc. I assume kolla was used for that? [{'created': '2015-04-29 20:50:04.000000000', 'message': "Containerized TripleO Overcloud.

This change adds a containerized version of the overcloud for TripleO.
It's still a work in progress but I figured I'd put it up so people can
comment on how they want to see this advance.  It is in working order
here but may require some tweaks to properly integrate with the devtest
setup.  Please see the README-containers.md file for more information
on how to set this up.

This is using a RHEL Atomic image for now and requires that we
bootstrap the image with a container which contains the os-* programs.

Change-Id: I8bbe75abc3f5e160bd4371710cbac236ba8eebc9
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Hallisey <rhallisey@redhat.com>
"}, {'created': '2015-05-08 19:38:51.000000000', 'message': "Containerized TripleO Overcloud.

This change adds a containerized version of the overcloud for TripleO.
It's still a work in progress but I figured I'd put it up so people can
comment on how they want to see this advance.  It is in working order
here but may require some tweaks to properly integrate with the devtest
setup.  Please see the README-containers.md file for more information
on how to set this up.

This is using a RHEL Atomic image for now and requires that we
bootstrap the image with a container which contains the os-* programs.

This version attempts to use the overcloud-without-mergepy with minimal
changes.  There is still some work to do here but we are close.  I
haven't addressed all the issues raised yet but will keep working on it.

Change-Id: I8bbe75abc3f5e160bd4371710cbac236ba8eebc9
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Hallisey <rhallisey@redhat.com>
"}, {'created': '2015-05-26 18:57:08.000000000', 'message': "Containerized TripleO Overcloud.

TripleO.  It's still a work in progress but I figured I'd put it up so people
can comment on how they want to see this advance.  Please see the
README-containers.md file for more information on how to set this up.

This uses AtomicOS as a base operating system and requires that we bootstrap
the image with a container which contains the os-* programs.

- Switch to kolla containers using delorean.
- Switch to docker-compose.
- Devtest scripting with switch to enable docker compute node.

commit_message:
Containerized TripleO Overcloud.

This change adds a containerized version of the overcloud compute node for
TripleO.  It's still a work in progress but I figured I'd put it up so people
can comment on how they want to see this advance.  Please see the
README-containers.md file for more information on how to set this up.

This uses AtomicOS as a base operating system and requires that we bootstrap
the image with a container which contains the os-* programs.

Change-Id: I8bbe75abc3f5e160bd4371710cbac236ba8eebc9
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Hallisey <rhallise@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I80dd7e183098d7265ac52da4445c1963dace7ffb

commit_message:
Make keepalived virtual router IDs configurable

Make the virtual router IDs configurable for the VRRP instances
associated with the Controller VIP or the Public VIP. This allows
side-by-side installations to work, as otherwise, the keepalived
clusters will interfere with each other and ultimately result in
failure to bring up a VIP.

Closes-Bug: 1396695
Co-authored-by: James Polley <jp@jamezpolley.com>
Change-Id: I659c116477d5a99ee6537e0fea80fdee7eaad909

commit_message:
Add metadata and change swift.devices to enable zones

This change adds metadata swift.zones and a corresponding
parameter SwiftZones to set the number of Swift zones to be used
when building the overcloud.  This number defaults to 1.  In
addition we change the swift.devices metadata to include the
server key - of the form controller|SwiftStorage<N> - between %-signs
which is used by the modified element
swift/os-refresh-config/configure.d/73-swift to place the server
in the appropriate zone.

Change-Id: I0e0f5189da1575f2e1ed7fba4bbbe13a8fbf6221

I don't want to get in the way of this landing if other people think it's useful, but I believe our goal is to only expose config options in t-h-t when they're things that we have to be able to configure in order to get a running cloud - everything else should be put in the extra_config and passed through, otherwise our het templates need to reflect every config option of every piece of software we ever install.

In this case, I don't understand why these options are neccessary to get a running cloud. In keeping with the first item of https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages#Information_in_commit_messages, "Do not assume that the reviwer understands what the problem was", I'd like it if the commit message here would describe what the problem was that made it neccessary to expose these values in the heat templates.'}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-12-10 17:58:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

I checked the referenced bug for more information, but it does not explain why these values are required, it merely says that rabbitmq uses these values.

I don't believe that justifies adding these into the heat templates - to me it sounds like this is a case where the values should be passed in via extra_config.

On that basis I'm going to give this a -1."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-08 14:39:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add Ceilometer configuration ttl setting for expirer

Adds the ttl settings for the Ceilometer expirer tool, defaulting to the
"-1" (retain all) value for the time-to-live for samples in the Ceilometer
database.

Change-Id: I6c7d4cb691c531fd7131e6c09235fe8074063191

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Ie3476db0bcc7f4ab08d64dd63e71958e8b3f5ab2

[{'created': '2014-07-24 09:19:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add SwiftRingBuild parameter

We want to add the facility to disable Swift ring building on nodes
running Swift.  To do this we add a parameter called SwiftRingBuild.
If this parameter is set to False or F, then the swift element will
not attempt to build the rings.  If this parameter is set to True
(the default) or T then the swift element will build the rings.

We want to allow an operator to turn off ring-building in the case
where new Swift nodes are being added to an existing Swift cluster.
In the absence of any tooling to help with ring management the
operator will have to use the default method of building new rings
to include the new nodes, and distributing the rings to the Swift
nodes - including existing nodes.

There is a corresponding element change, see
https://review.openstack.org/109029

'}]
commit_message:
Add SwiftRingBuild parameter

We want to add the facility to disable Swift ring building on nodes
running Swift.  To do this we add a parameter called SwiftRingBuild.
If this parameter is set to False or F, then the swift element will
not attempt to build the rings.  If this parameter is set to True
(the default) or T then the swift element will build the rings.

We want to allow an operator to turn off ring-building in the case
where new Swift nodes are being added to an existing Swift cluster.
In the absence of any tooling to help with ring management the
operator will have to use the default method of building new rings
to include the new nodes, and distributing the rings to the Swift
nodes - including existing nodes.

There is a corresponding element change, see
https://review.openstack.org/109029

Change-Id: I01311ec3ca265b151f8740bf7dc57cdf0cf0df6f

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I57549c6731e7479da9ac9c1f1dbe37140312f0a8

commit_message:
Add ironic_base test case

 Scenario:
  1. Create cluster
  2. Add 1 controller node
  3. Add 1 compute node
  4. Add 1 ironic node
  5. Launch OSTF tests

Partially Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic

Change-Id: I3a5b15f61d41ab7936de684166eacd542c00e0de

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Id00869faee250e37b7217357e39bc5fbda567a55

(7 comments)

Few more review comments.

To qualify my "doesn't work" comment, there's some logs pasted into the README, the issue is the nova-compute service doesn't start inside the nova-compute container - there's a bunch of libvirt errors, and attempting to nova-boot a VM on the deployed overcloud fails.

If we can fix that, and the other minor things, I'm +2 on this'}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2015-09-30 19:17:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

There's a version issue between nova-compute and libvirt.  Kolla must've rebuilt from underneath us.  We're going to move to stable/liberty"}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2015-09-30 21:17:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

Turns out... the controller node has been recently updated where the controller node is not compatible with the version of libvirt in the compute node.  That explains why were never saw this and it crept up on us over time.  The images just need to be updated.  We will bump the tag to stable liberty with the addition of json config generation that kolla requires in a following patch.  For now we just need to rebuild the images.'}, {'account_id': 2011, 'date': '2015-09-30 21:53:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

It's the nova controller and compute that are version mismatched.. amqp object version mismatch errors."}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2015-10-01 02:28:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

(10 comments)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-10-01 09:52:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

>  Kolla must've rebuilt from underneath us. We're going to move to stable/liberty

This actually raises an interesting question - how do we intend to maintain these images?

E.g, we have delorean to maintain RPM packages for everything from trunk (and, ref my release branch spec, potentially for stable/liberty too), but I'm not sure how we'll do that for containers?

E.g, the current TripleO model is to deploy latest master of everything, but it sounds like you're going to switch to using stable/liberty containers, which while also being something we do probably want to support, is inconsistent with what non-docker TripleO deployments actually contain."}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2015-10-01 12:03:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

That theory turned out not be true. Kolla doesn't rebuild the images once we tag the release.  We just push once.  The issue turned out to be tripleo changing in master.

With regards to your questions.  
a) We could either build the images ourselves upon startup, which would get us latest packages.  I don't like this because we don't want the images to change unless we have update them.
b) We rebuild custom images and push it to the tripleo docker hub as we need them.  I'd imagine we will only need to do this occasionally for nova-compute and possibly others if something drastically changes.  So only do this if we have to."}, {'account_id': 2011, 'date': '2015-10-01 15:49:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

The original idea was to build them daily or such.  The issue we're running into here is that the controller is still managed as before, using latest master upstream while the containers we are using are older.  It's definitely an issue we need to address."}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2015-10-01 20:00:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

(2 comments)

The docs nits are still there from the previous revision, but basically this lgtm - I pulled and tested it, it works!

I deployed an overcloud and booted a cirros image on the deployed nova.

The main problem is the overcloud create takes over twice as long as a normal puppet based deployment (on a pretty fast internet connection), IMO we must find ways to optimize that, but I'm not blocking on it as clearly we can land this then iterate to make it faster."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-08 13:28:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

(8 comments)

great to see this working!

i made some notes inline. i just wanted to make sure to point out what i saw. i think the level of workarounds and "hacks" are ok for now, but not something we'd want to see stick around for long.

anyway, i know everyone is already planning on iterating to address these items in the short term.

a few other things:

This doesnt work with network isolation. I tried with the single-nic-with-vlans templates, and the compute node just dropped all networking when /usr/local/bin/os-net-config got run.

Although I could launch a cirros image at the end, I was not able to ping the floating ip I assigned to it. I didn't see any obvious errors (nothing in openvswitch agent log, etc).

I'd really love to see this covered by CI. Even with the workarounds and hacks that are there now. It's a lot of work to set this up and test manually :). I don't see how else we're going to have confidence that changes we're making aren't breaking this. We want to make sure we aren't making changes to tripleo-heat-templates in general for the puppet implementation that aren't constantly breaking the docker implementation and vice-versa.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-10-09 19:08:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-09 19:08:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: -Verified

commit_message:
Docker compute role configured via Puppet

This change adds a containerized version of the overcloud compute node for
TripleO. Configuration files are generated via OpenStack Puppet modules
which are then used to externally configure kolla containers for
each OpenStack service.

See the README-containers.md file for more information on how to set this up.

This uses AtomicOS as a base operating system and requires that we bootstrap
the image with a container which contains the required os-collect-config agent
hooks to support running puppet, shell scripts, and docker compose.

Change-Id: Ic8331f52b20a041803a9d74cdf0eb81266d4e03c
Co-Authored-By: Ian Main <imain@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Hallisey <rhallise@redhat.com>
