commit_message:
Provide minimum VIOS connection on vSCSI volumes

When the admin attempts to connect a volume, they may wish to specify a
minimum level of redundancy (how many Virtual I/O Servers it connects
to).  This change set provides the operator with the ability to set a
minimum number of VIOSes.

Change-Id: Id4d4ca945190f04436792cac12fa08f4412bc114
Closes-Bug: 1504037

commit_message:
Remove openstack_deploy from teardown.sh deletion list

This patch prevents teardown.sh script from deleting
/etc/openstack_deploy in order to let the deployer decide whether to
delete it or not.

Change-Id: I8de55c6fce79bd9301d995c565cfb4e0a38b253a
Closes-Bug: #1504561

[{'created': '2015-10-09 05:45:36.000000000', 'message': "Update dhcp host portbinding on failover

When a dhcp server is moved to new host on failover,
tunnel is not created.

When a dhcp server is moved to new host,
1) network-hostagent binding is updated(properly i.e with new host).
2) dhcp port-hostagent binding is not updated
   ( dhcp port is still bound to old host)
If dhcp port-bound agent is different from the new dhcp agent
(which is now taking care of this dhcp port), neutron plugin won't
 notify the l2pop, and hence tunnel is not created.

As after failover, the new agent is taking care of this dhcp port,
update portbinding with the new host. This will allow neutron plugin
to notify l2pop(which will create tunnel).

Change-Id: Ib7d7dcddee005395af116ccd31a43853332ae317
Closes-bug: #1411163
(cherry picked from commit 571453c614577ffd47e23de9a35863d2f2119583)
"}]
commit_message:
Update dhcp host portbinding on failover

When a dhcp server is moved to new host on failover,
tunnel is not created.

When a dhcp server is moved to new host,
1) network-hostagent binding is updated(properly i.e with new host).
2) dhcp port-hostagent binding is not updated
   ( dhcp port is still bound to old host)
If dhcp port-bound agent is different from the new dhcp agent
(which is now taking care of this dhcp port), neutron plugin won't
 notify the l2pop, and hence tunnel is not created.

As after failover, the new agent is taking care of this dhcp port,
update portbinding with the new host. This will allow neutron plugin
to notify l2pop(which will create tunnel).

Change-Id: Ib7d7dcddee005395af116ccd31a43853332ae317
Closes-bug: #1411163
(cherry picked from commit 571453c614577ffd47e23de9a35863d2f2119583)

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I14b2242c93518793988496386f9eb08aabc3afb4

commit_message:
Add config-openwrt-with-firewall file to samples

This patchset adds the openwrt config yaml to devstack samples
directory. This file can be used to try out the openwrt config
update using the --config-file attribute during vnf-create and
vnf-update.

Change-Id: Ie1f30f169e5edef47405f68bc1a156bc8dc283d9

[{'created': '2015-10-08 03:47:27.000000000', 'message': "Use LOG.error when no exception handler is used

There's no need to use LOG.exception here since sys.exc_info()
results in (None, None, None) and thus would effectively just
be LOG.error.

Also, the failure of invoking LOG.exception outside of an

commit_message:
Use LOG.error when no exception handler is used

There's no need to use LOG.exception here since sys.exc_info()
results in (None, None, None) and thus would effectively just
be LOG.error.

Also, the failure of invoking LOG.exception outside of an
exception handler is due to a bug in Python3[1]. The fix for
that is only available in Python3.5.

[1] http://bugs.python.org/issue17911

Closes-Bug: #1482261

Change-Id: I9ceac0fceafa45769cc15f56027c981182ff0750

commit_message:
Remove unused variables

* Both BIRD and BIRDC are defined but now used everywhere
* METADATA_PROXY is not used everywhere and is pointing to
  the wrong binary. metadata_proxy has been renamed to
  akanda-metadata_proxy.

Change-Id: Ie0888a80df6561cb65c27a2048d75edbe95a3971
Signed-off-by: Rosario Di Somma <rosario.disomma@dreamhost.com>

commit_message:
Change string generation mechanism for info logging

As stated in Openstack logging and i18n guidelines it is
recommended that formatted string for log messages should be
generated by logger (not by logger client/user). In this case
we can skip formatted message generation if log level configured
not to show info messages.
Also some non-used initialization of logger has been deleted
from the code.

Change-Id: I25660395417ea288aee6a70609a5336e6f74c291

commit_message:
Include scenario test for checking VPN status

1. Validate the VPN-service and ipsec-site connection status
when updating the router status to DOWN and back to ACTIVE state
2. Added methods in vpn_base to support this scenario test
3. Modified test_vpn_connectivity test because of [2]
4. Updated rally_config file to include this scenario test

Change-Id: I72b53b2e01779d57e9ccac0e9c7155d9a8e4e877

commit_message:
Improve documentation for Liberty release

The documentation cross linking from the devstack rst to the
individual plugins is missing due to the devstack rst living
in a different directory. We just need to provide a bit better
linking from devstack as well as a bit more info on each plugin
for where to place to the configuration options for each plugin.

There is also opportunity to make the documentation between
plugins more consistent and provide release note information.

Change-Id: Ib64eeda8a9f5b59777135537de60f049952a4660
Closes-Bug: #1500647

"}, {'created': '2015-09-22 01:23:44.000000000', 'message': "Start of the LBAAS driver

This is the start of the LBAAS driver.  If you point [lbaas] config
at the existing akanda appliance image, it should spin up a new instance
on and manage the neutron resource's state according to the akanda resource.

This LB driver expects to be able to push its config to the akanda-appliance
server running in the image, and that server is responsible for translating
what the RUG gives it to something suitable for the LB service installed in
that image.  There will be a corresponding change to akanda-appliance for this.

The port creation currently creates a instance port on the same network as the
LB VIP.  I'm not sure what else we need to do in terms of port plugging.

List of other things that have been done:

    - Split akanda.rug.api.configuration into akanda-rug.api.config.{common,
      router} in prep for building LBAAS configs as well.
    - Build configuration for both routers and LBs using their own respective
      config libraries, but push to the same appliance via the /v1/system/

TODO:
    - Figure out correct port plugging
    - Subscribe to other LBAAS events and translate those into config updates

This requires a corresponding change to akanda-neutron to enable
the akloadbalancerstatus api extension.

Change-Id: Ic19a883f56fb6d65a83b1f4d93b581f9e242d97f
"}, {'created': '2015-09-22 05:51:11.000000000', 'message': "Start of the LBAAS driver

at the existing akanda appliance image, it should spin up a new instance
on and manage the neutron resource's state according to the akanda resource.

"}, {'created': '2015-09-23 01:48:13.000000000', 'message': "Start of the LBAAS driver

This is the start of the LBAAS driver.  If you point [lbaas] config
at the existing akanda appliance image, it should spin up a new instance
on and manage the neutron resource's state according to the akanda resource.

This LB driver expects to be able to push its config to the akanda-appliance
server running in the image, and that server is responsible for translating
what the RUG gives it to something suitable for the LB service installed in
that image.  There will be a corresponding change to akanda-appliance for this.

The drivers port creation callback currently creates a instance port on the
same network as the LB VIP and auths it as an allowed adddress pair. During
config push to the appliance, we include the VIP port in the configs'
interface map so as to bring up the VIP on the right interface. Note this currently
does not instruct the appliance to bring up the actual address we create for it.

List of other things that have been done:

    - Split akanda.rug.api.configuration into akanda-rug.api.config.{common,
      router} in prep for building LBAAS configs as well.
    - Build configuration for both routers and LBs using their own respective
      config libraries, but push to the same appliance via the /v1/system/
    - Updates most/all neutron objects to have a to_dict() method to make
      it easier to serialize for shipping to the appliance.
    - Wraps instance_manager's configure() with a driver status sync--the LBAAS
      resource needs to be synced everytime we update one of its child resources
      otherwise it waits in PENDING_UPDATE forever.

TODO:
    - Manage neutron status for all child resources (members, listeners, etc)

This requires a corresponding change to akanda-neutron to enable
the akloadbalancerstatus api extension.

Change-Id: Ic19a883f56fb6d65a83b1f4d93b581f9e242d97f

commit_message:
Adds an LBAAS driver

This is the start of the LBAAS driver.  If you point [lbaas] config
at the existing akanda appliance image, it should spin up a new instance
on and manage the neutron resource's state according to the akanda resource.

This LB driver expects to be able to push its config to the akanda-appliance
server running in the image, and that server is responsible for translating
what the RUG gives it to something suitable for the LB service installed in
that image.  There will be a corresponding change to akanda-appliance for this.

The drivers port creation callback currently creates a instance port on the
same network as the LB VIP and auths it as an allowed adddress pair. During
config push to the appliance, we include the VIP port in the configs'
interface map so as to bring up the VIP on the right interface. Note this currently
does not instruct the appliance to bring up the actual address we create for it.

This requires a corresponding change to akanda-neutron to enable
the akloadbalancerstatus api extension: http://review.openstack.org/#/c/225370/

And also a change to akanda-appliance: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/226119/

Implements: blueprint lbaas-v2-support

Change-Id: Ic19a883f56fb6d65a83b1f4d93b581f9e242d97f

'}, {'created': '2015-09-21 14:56:04.000000000', 'message': 'Enable password_config_option_not_marked_secret Bandit test

The password_config_option_not_marked_secret test checks that
"password" config options have secret=True. The instance of a
password option that's not marked secret is not holding a password

commit_message:
Enable password_config_option_not_marked_secret Bandit test

The password_config_option_not_marked_secret test checks that
"password" config options have secret=True. The instance of a
password option that's not marked secret is not holding a password
but the entrypoint for the password auth plugin.

Change-Id: I09355f50269719d173a0bdfc1ea22f8cf9a1cf04

commit_message:
Remove an oslo.message 2.2.0 pin

In https://bugs.launchpad.net/kolla/+bug/1483667, oslo.messaging
was pinned to 2.2.0.  This pin is no longer necessary as this bug
has been fixed upstream.

backport: liberty

TrivialFix

Change-Id: Ica9ae41876a754291d4c6ee1235f6e69a4213463
(cherry picked from commit 52eb4d84034ade58cb108fa19f2aa6562d9b82e5)

commit_message:
Remove debug output in base image yum command

The base image contains -d 10 in a yum command which prints unhelpful
debug output for one of the yum commands.  Remove the extranous debug
output.

backport: liberty

TrivialFix

This patch is a trivial fix and is a test to set boundaries on what
a trivial fix looks like that doesn't require a bug tracker entry.  If
reviewers feel a trivial fix isn't documented properly by this commit
message, please weigh in, as this is a slight suggested change to our
policy as first institued by the Magnum community and brought to my
attention by Jeff Peeler.  Hopefully this compromise won't be abused :)

Change-Id: I57f00978d0baaefd73592f4ad6a655e663d83478
(cherry picked from commit 8137be87b55e1c9971060d31c85d3a5aa1644b7e)

commit_message:
Install agent dependencies from source for CentOS

Several packages are not installed from RPM packages which are
required in order for CentOS from source to operate correctly.

This looked like sudo was failing to execute, but it was because
the dnsmasq binary was not found.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: If23cfbacd55d9089ffec442399ee0151adea923f
Closes-Bug: #1503412
(cherry picked from commit bc0f8b422ad8a49d59ab2a504a108554cc75cbc0)

commit_message:
Removing /dev/log on rsyslog start

Currently we seem to be experiencing races between containers.
If another containers tries to write to rsyslog before rsyslog container
is up and running it will create /dev/log as directory,
and that will prevent rsyslog from starting.

Change-Id: I88ac27693d12e605f95e3a945fc98783516d7933
Closes-Bug: #1501694
backport: liberty
(cherry picked from commit 7d6621e68bd1be200afc33b9952ce40cb877b793)

commit_message:
Fix up ironic Dockerfiles to build

The dockerfiles for each of these containers were hacked to force
install the most recent version of the package, even though the newer
version had a lower version number. Delorean has fixed the issue by
bumping the epoch, so the hack is no longer required.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I8d9c071d84e53280d3cadfceb9034bb96f64f3a3
Closes-bug: #1503785
(cherry picked from commit 556597b1116a2e6a7ab6deb3a38a075d6b46dd54)

[{'created': '2015-10-08 21:43:15.000000000', 'message': "Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I22ce72a855bc9a2fce396a1d3f109c1f97615d4c
"}]
commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I22ce72a855bc9a2fce396a1d3f109c1f97615d4c

commit_message:
Release version 1.0.0

Our current version based upon conversations with TTX was
0.1.0. It appears now that the full API is nearly stable.  It is
stable enough to call our first Liberty release 1.0.0.

The API consists of the following data:
The locations of config files passed to the container
The environment variables expected by the container
The JSON encoded file containing the copy and cmd operations

Each container in current master follows the same sytnax and
style for all of the implementations of every container that
atleast has been Ansibilized.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I2064689ca6fd9f332ad26624e1b93f6aaa08e79b
Closes-Bug: #1503494
(cherry picked from commit 418428a1ad6bd681e9a240689741c49b9111b0d5)

(14 comments)

I don't think you still need {{ container_config_directory }} in any o fthose json files but I am not certain, so can you double check.  If I am wrong, please let me know on irc and I'll change my vote."}, {'account_id': 1390, 'date': '2015-10-09 09:28:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'm not 100% on the layout of the config files, always found it a little confusing, so am open to correction.

The reason I didn't remove {{ container_config_directory }} for the non ring files is due to the way the volumes are mounted in start.yml.  e.g. for the proxy-server:

    volumes:
        - "{{ node_config_directory }}/swift/:/var/lib/kolla/swift/:ro"
        - "{{ node_config_directory }}/swift-proxy-server/:{{ container_config_directory }}/:ro"

The first mount is hard coded to /var/lib/kolla/swift, which is where the files common to all swift services such as the rings, are located.

The second mount is for swift-proxy-server specific confs, and could potentially change if someone overrides {{ container_config_directory }}. So if I hardcode /var/lib/kolla/swift for proxy-server.conf, and someone changes container_config_directory, it will break.'}, {'account_id': 10787, 'date': '2015-10-09 10:00:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

sdake: config directory is for configs, but binaries and blobs in var/lib/kolla. At least that's what I did in rsyslog. I actually think it's good but not 100% sure so just +1"}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:35:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I am pretty sure this is correct sdake.

Swift is a bit weird due to the double mount for config/rings. I am working on handling that for the mitaka cycle here (and updating all the config copying to be more.... helpful).

If this works for you pbourke, I am a-ok with it.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-10-09 17:57:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Swift JSON files looking for rings in the wrong place

For Swift, the *.json.j2 templates are looking under
{{ container_config_directory }} whereas they need to be looking in the
common location for swift which is /var/lib/kolla/swift

Change-Id: I6f0dcbc9a705b36d1d98275ba9ebc56404fe882d
backport: liberty
Closes-Bug: #1504210

[{'created': '2015-10-08 21:43:58.000000000', 'message': "Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I4f5b3df5c00bca02af401fd458a20aaa07ee560d
"}]
commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I4f5b3df5c00bca02af401fd458a20aaa07ee560d

commit_message:
Case insensitiveness when comparing choices values

This path is adding a flag called "ignore_case" for the StrOpt type which
allow case insensitiveness for 'choices' and 'regex' values. The flag
receives a boolean value and if True, the case differences (uppercase
vs. lowercase) between the values of choices will be ignored. It defaults
to False.

This flag is important because it helps with backward compability of a
StrOpt configuration that before accepted case insensitive and now is
using 'choices'

Change-Id: I5f68eee59588dd2be62e11491ad73d452bc9fc07

commit_message:
Code coverage fix and devstack fix

Checkin gates are failing (both coverage and integration/tempest)

Handling the case where testr fails by exiting and returning the
exit status. Newest 'coverage' package does not support 'ignore-errors'
in config section '[report]'.

Also updating devstack plugins/scripts to use updated keystone v3
compatible commands (openstack vs nova)

Change-Id: I06d4e1179f115220608bcb15bbcfccc96769e11e

commit_message:
Enable extend_share in HDFS driver

The extend_share is in Manila core, we can support the new API in
the HDFS drivers. This patch adds methods to the driver along with
its unit tests, and updates related docs.

Implements: blueprint hdfs-native-extend-share

Change-Id: Ia81291eda49dc20c3318f71c51d36682d2aae742

commit_message:
Make CacheIsolatingProxy public

CacheIsolatingProxy was in the tests, but it should be available to
applications since it's useful to use in their own tests when
setting up the environment for caching.

[{'created': '2015-10-09 13:44:13.000000000', 'message': 'Redirect "apt-get install -y" stdin to /dev/null

According to debian bug 728775 [1] apt-get by design will consume stdin
(even when not run interactively).

When the run-aio-build.sh script is used as part of a curl-pipe-bash
such as described in the quick start docs [2] apt-get will effectively
halt execution of the script after installing git. The next time the
script is run it will get past the step because git is now installed and
apt-get no longer consumes stdin. In addition to run-aio-build.sh,
bootstrap-aio.sh and bootstrap-ansible.sh call apt-get and so exhibit
the same behaviour when called by run-aio-build.sh when used as part of
a curl-pipe-bash.

In addition to apt-get install -y, apt-get purge -y exhibits the same
behaviour.

The result for the end user is they must run the command multiple times
to get it to work.

out "E: Write error - write (14: Bad address)" and fail. The solution is
to explicitly set stdin to nothing, such as "echo '' | apt-get ..." or

yum install -y does not exhibit this behaviour and so does not require
its stdin redirected.

[1] https://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=728775
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/openstack-ansible/developer-docs/quickstart-aio.html#running-an-aio-build-in-one-step

Closes-Bug: 1504546

commit_message:
Redirect "apt-get install -y" stdin to /dev/null

According to debian bug 728775 [1] apt-get by design will consume stdin
(even when not run interactively).

When the run-aio-build.sh script is used as part of a curl-pipe-bash
such as described in the quick start docs [2] apt-get will effectively
halt execution of the script after installing git. The next time the
script is run it will get past the step because git is now installed and
apt-get no longer consumes stdin. In addition to run-aio-build.sh,
bootstrap-aio.sh and bootstrap-ansible.sh call apt-get and so exhibit
the same behaviour when called by run-aio-build.sh when used as part of
a curl-pipe-bash.

In addition to apt-get install -y, apt-get purge -y exhibits the same
behaviour.

The result for the end user is they must run the command multiple times
to get it to work.

Using the bash method to close stdin (0<&- [3]) causes apt-get to print
out "E: Write error - write (14: Bad address)" and fail. The solution is
to explicitly set stdin to nothing, such as "echo '' | apt-get ..." or
"apt-get ... < /dev/null". The latter is chosen for its aesthetics.

yum install -y does not exhibit this behaviour and so does not require
its stdin redirected.

[1] https://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=728775
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/openstack-ansible/developer-docs/quickstart-aio.html#running-an-aio-build-in-one-step
[3] http://www.tldp.org/LDP/abs/html/io-redirection.html

Change-Id: I57484590e257956e1d1bc8e10ce8a35207622672
Closes-Bug: 1504546

commit_message:
Documentation: Syntax checking before running playbooks

This brings:
1) A new page to explain how can a deployer test its
configuration files.

2) Links on the pages mentionning the playbooks that
traditionally has errors because of the deployer's config.

Change-Id: I434152a14de806e24e5886969dfa15e3ff1c4928
(cherry picked from commit 8edf7fe90c88ca3b122b35a5031f78619e13aac3)

commit_message:
Stale OF entries retained in br-int

The del-manager was triggered from the plugin.sh script
before deleting the neutron ports. This was the reason for
unicast mac flows not getting removed. Fixed it by first
delting the neutron port and then deleting the ovs contoller
configuration.

(cherry picked from commit 3bed954972050ceb74dd6e340e542bcf94091a7f)

Change-Id: Iab0c727a274880c736e3ff591459dc4f77c9e849
Signed-off-by: mailravi02 <mailravi02@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Expose Znode Stats and Capabilities

Expose Znode statistics like creation time, update time,
number of children and capabilities(data). This is useful
when the consumer say Nova Servicegroup wants to make
decision based of the content of the Znode information.

Change-Id: I3da8fc0e2c76d83dbd2133bb8a41cc1ffeb6d807
Closes-Bug: #1493990

So it seems there is some other repo providing an old Ironic rpm, because if we disable all repos except the ones we are intentionally using we get the right version.

The root of the issue is the package from the rogue repo is from before the switch to semver, so it looks like a newer version.

The proper fix is to add epoch to the Ironic packaging so that the semver packages are newer than the old date versioned packages. commit_message:
Add ironic-inspector support

Add the ability to configure the ironic-inspector service
for doing introspection of bare metal nodes.

Closes-Bug: 1486197
Change-Id: I9b2917a2c3f6afe75dc295c81d09f7a12856007f

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-09 16:11:58.000000000', 'message': "Remove compose from the repostiory since its dead code

Several people over the liberty cycle committed to maintaining
compose, but it was never completed.  Rather than carry compose
in our repoistory until the end of time in a broken state I propose
removing it.  If someone comes along and wants to resseruct the code
and make it functional in the future, I'd be 100% open to merge a
patch in the future which reintroduces this functionality.  In the
meantime it is confusing to users which ask me on a daily basis if
compose is supported which I have to go into a 10 minute monologue
about why its in the repository.

Fortunately git contains full history so we can always revert this

commit_message:
Remove compose from the repostiory since its dead code

Several people over the liberty cycle committed to maintaining
compose, but it was never completed.  Rather than carry compose
in our repoistory until the end of time in a broken state I propose
removing it.  If someone comes along and wants to resseruct the code
and make it functional in the future, I'd be 100% open to merge a
patch in the future which reintroduces this functionality.  In the
meantime it is confusing to users which ask me on a daily basis if
compose is supported which I have to go into a 10 minute monologue
about why its in the repository.

Fortunately git contains full history so we can always revert this
change at a later time if someone wants to actually fixt his code
base up and make it useable in some way.  I think the proper answer
is a seperate repoistory (kolla-compose) which contains any compose
related bits.

Please consider removing since nobody is using this code and its
dead.

TrivialFix

backport: liberty
Change-Id: I8b7c39b00d1967184d363af7db86d1ff8b5e725f
(cherry picked from commit ed2f908a4cb5f4dd36e21fd8f32317f7f94df4bf)

commit_message:
Add mtime to generated indexes

It is valuable when looking for the most recent test run to know the mod
time of log files. Add this to the generated index files to provide that
information to our users.

Change-Id: I03669afd73d1f0ce14adce17a3136ce26377b403

commit_message:
Stale OF entries retained in br-int

The del-manager was triggered from the plugin.sh script
before deleting the neutron ports. This was the reason for
unicast mac flows not getting removed. Fixed it by first
delting the neutron port and then deleting the ovs contoller
configuration.
Change-Id: Iab0c727a274880c736e3ff591459dc4f77c9e849
Signed-off-by: mailravi02 <mailravi02@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Updates to network documentation for new features

This change contains fixes to the network documentation as well as
additions of the creation of floating IP and provider networks.
The bonding information was also significantly updated. All references
to --plan overcloud were replaced with --templates. A bug in the docs
referenced an incorrect way to define the NeutronExternalNetworkBridge,
this is fixed now.

Change-Id: Ia2d609c8386f8cf90edb1a0ff57691df88b83aab

Base akanda driver

Abstract driver class that illustrates the minimum expected of methods
for an akanda driver.

Partially Implements: blueprint appliance-provisioning-driver
Change-Id: Iaa94a5d5c3adea995e0a581665e67b7396062a00

commit_message:
Use tool method instead of random.randint for consistency

In neutron/tests/base.py, randint of random module is used
although tools (already imported) has method for randint.
It's duplicated. This replaces random.randint with
get_random_integer so that neutron code gets consistent.

Change-Id: Ied5c46aa2267115ab74afa098fe7eb115c7a3e16

commit_message:
Return full structure of std info in Linux class methods

This patch adds to 'putFile' and 'runCommand' methods ability to return
full structure containing stdout, stderr and exitcode instead of
returning just exitCode, which worked incorrectly.

New optional parameter 'options' was added to allow specifing custom
options execution plans.

Change-Id: Icb2b9c5cc72a4555ccee85c471547041be86e2fc
Closes-Bug: #1504211

commit_message:
Return full structure of std info in Linux class methods

This patch adds to 'putFile' and 'runCommand' methods ability to return
full structure containing stdout, stderr and exitcode instead of
returning just exitCode, which worked incorrectly.

New optional parameter 'options' was added to allow specifing custom
options execution plans.

Change-Id: Icb2b9c5cc72a4555ccee85c471547041be86e2fc
Closes-Bug: #1504211

commit_message:
Switch cinder to use os_service_default fact

This change switches the cinder module to use the os_service_default
fact for configuration options that default to '<SERVICE DEFAULT>'.

Change-Id: I8c28f02794fdc7034a85eab80a66a98f664380ea
Depends-On: Ieeb92b4e7fbb556a8d32682fb24284091227c991

commit_message:
Use non-absolute url, when composing repository urls

This commit changes urls in the path of the to_url to be non-absolute,
to allow urlparse lib concatenate path and MURANO_REPO_URL with
a non-empty path component correctly.

Also monkey-patches from_location and ensure_images to ensure, that they
also use non-absolute urls.

Change-Id: I4fd2b1001e05de79b0d1813790f7c61518f1a90f
Closes-Bug: #1503593

commit_message:
Rename stackforge/os-ansible-deployment{,specs}

In Id3f6175fcdd4a21019eabca56cd337145ff9c2b0 os-ansible-deployment moved
into the openstack namespace and was renamed to
openstack/openstack-ansible. It's specs repository will also be renamed
to openstack/openstack-ansible-specs.

This also switches the publishing of documentation from readthedocs to
docs.openstack.org and includes both doc and spec publishing.

Change-Id: I10588f1118f21793ef9a1a647184cf2e8de07260

commit_message:
Broader find_vios commands

Multiple flows need to find the VIOS hosting a port map.  Unfortunately,
one can't always be guaranteed to have a physical port (e.g. live
migration may have source physical wwpn instead of target) or virtual
ports (e.g. spawn would have physical but not yet virtual).

This change set enables more of nova-powervm to use capabilities within
pypowervm to do the broader port_map contextual search.  This should
improve stability of npiv when using functions like live_migration, or
also when rolling back a spawn due to issues.

Change-Id: I0789f17c02e9fa92e88df76873c9aba4b07cc41a

commit_message:

'True' instead of 'true' which is wrong syntax for MuranoPL.

Closes-Bug: #1504050

commit_message:
Make javascript jobs on openstack-health non-voting

These jobs don't even come close to working. npm is going out to the
internet to pull packages and it is failing to download packages. This
is causing everything to fail before it even gets started. This commit
makes these jobs non-voting, it would have been good to have voting
coverage on the js in the repo, but if the jobs can't reliable pull in
requirements we can only use them as advisory jobs.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-10 04:38:34.000000000', 'message': 'Filter get_pool_members to return only members from the desired pool

Calls to "neutron lbaas-member-list <pool_id>" are currently returning
all members from every pool, not just those belonging to <pool_id>.
There is no filter being passed to the database query for pool
members.

This fix creates a filter for <pool_id>.

Change-Id: I206e5fca06e2e4322c42737a98a4cfa5c055101e
Closes-Bug: #1483100

commit_message:
Filter get_pool_members to return members from the desired pool

Calls to "neutron lbaas-member-list <pool_id>" are currently returning
all members from every pool, not just those belonging to <pool_id>.
There is no filter being passed to the database query for pool
members.

This fix creates a filter for <pool_id>.

Change-Id: I206e5fca06e2e4322c42737a98a4cfa5c055101e
Closes-Bug: #1483100
Co-Authored-By: Brandon Logan <brandon.logan@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Dev-ref update

This change set provides a significant update to the nova-powervm
drivers dev-ref.

Rebases the documentation to reflect the development that has been done
over the last several months.  Updates the readme to reflect the
execution that has completed.

Removes the fake_driver that is not useful.

Change-Id: I1910db886df89f884f3c399d6aab1eebdf10b5e0

commit_message:
Handle empty bridge case in OVSBridge.get_ports_attributes

Before this patch, get_ports_attributes would call
get_port_name_list. In the case of an empty bridge,
get_port_name_list would return an empty list and feed that
in to ovsdb.db_list, thereby returning all ports instead of
no ports.

Change-Id: I5a91028c59d71943b7cef86a94fa6ab1cc3d667c
Closes-Bug: #1499821

commit_message:
Update nova & tempest SHA's and remove django-openstack-auth SHA

This patch updates the nova and tempest SHA's to address more issues
found in Liberty testing.

It also removes the git-based pin for django-openstack-auth and
instead implements a lower cap for the package which includes the
appropriate fix.

Closes-Bug: #1497679

Adding modularization for neutron setup for master.

- Core Plugin can be selected by name, and new ones added to the
  'plugins_neutron' data structure
- Agents are enabled/disabled through 'services_neutron' dict
  in roles/os_neutron/defaults/main.yml
- Upstart tasks for agentss are run based on individual enabled status
- Agent service names propagate to appropiate handler

Note: The current implementation can be further optimized when

      reduced to a single task that loops on the neutron_services
      dict.

commit_message:
[backport] Modularizing Neutron playbooks for master

Adding modularization for neutron setup for master.

- Core Plugin can be selected by name, and new ones added to the
  'plugins_neutron' data structure
- Agents are enabled/disabled through 'services_neutron' dict
  in roles/os_neutron/defaults/main.yml
- Upstart tasks for agentss are run based on individual enabled status
- Agent service names propagate to appropiate handler

Note: The current implementation can be further optimized when
      we move to ansible-v2. The neutron_upstart_init.yml can be
      reduced to a single task that loops on the neutron_services
      dict.

Implements: blueprint modularize-neutron-liberty

Change-Id: I655921835b9b47bc6381ac6ca0dd46d4a7bc2bbd
Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>

commit_message:
Change router unbinding logic to be consistent with data model

Model allows router to be bound to different agents
Code should not make assumptions that the correspondence is 1-to-1

Closes-Bug: #1497980
Change-Id: Ieda9fc6e2d5a85194f2d022ea092cefb55183750

Ironic(Id9645e06eb707ef21a7cb99c420309f54a95aa9b already merged).  Initially,
I had thought to be completed in the following modification.

  diff --git a/ironic/drivers/modules/console_utils.py b/ironic/drivers/modules/console_utils.py
  index b4172a9..31d7c1a 100644
  --- a/ironic/drivers/modules/console_utils.py
  +++ b/ironic/drivers/modules/console_utils.py
  @@ -135,7 +135,7 @@ def make_persistent_password_file(path, password):
           utils.delete_if_exists(path)
           with open(path, 'wb') as file:
               os.chmod(path, 0o600)
  -            file.write(password.encode())
  +            file.write(str(password).encode())
           return path
       except Exception as e:
           utils.delete_if_exists(path)

However, after a while, I noticed that the integrity of the string is lost when
it is converted to a numeric type.  For example, the password of "65432.10" is
considered to be a decimal when converting to a numeric type, IPMI driver will
receive the string "65432.1".  It means that the password that is different
from the specified string is passed to IPMI.  In other words, it must be
password is treated as a string from the beginning to the end.  Therefore, in
this modification, at the point where API receives a password first time, it
was to be treated as explicitly string.
(python_ironicclient must be fixed separately, For now I will fix the API earlier.)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-18 16:08:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

[{'created': '2015-09-04 03:33:26.000000000', 'message': "Fix a bug error by passwords includes just numbers

When IPMI passwords includes just numbers is used, it failed to create a
password file. From the format point of view, these passwords are
correct. These are that it is stored to the variable after being
converted to an int type, cause errors in the subsequent processing to
expect that it is a string type.

Also, if it begins with '0', it is interpreted as an octal number,
totally become a different value. In addition, an error occurs if it
contains a number of '8' or more. Therefore, when storing a password
from the DB variable, and by storing in a variable by explicitly
indicating the string type, to avoid problems.

Also for the user name, exactly the same cause, exactly in the same
place, in order to suffer exactly the same problem, to fix at the same
time.

Change-Id: I85ee2e904fdb0d538f69c7dbfab4c81bb080b8cf
Closes-Bug: #1489234

commit_message:
Fix a bug error by passwords only includes numbers

When an IPMI password consists only of numbers, Ironic fails to create a
password file. From the format point of view, these passwords are
correct. These are that it is stored to the variable after being
converted to an int type, cause errors in the subsequent processing to
expect that it is a string type.

Change-Id: I85ee2e904fdb0d538f69c7dbfab4c81bb080b8cf
Closes-Bug: #1489234

commit_message:
Mask passwords when logging the HTTP response

We should sanitize the response body before logging to make sure we
aren't leaking through credentials like in the case of the response from
the os-initialize_connection volume API.

Closes-Bug: #1490693

Change-Id: Ifd95d3fb624b4636fb72cc11762af62e00a026a0

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
usage_audit: Fix usage_audit to work with ML2

The script didn't work with the ML2 plugin as router related
functionality is moved to the L3 router service plugin. The fix assumes
that the L3 router service plugin is in use, and this seems to apply to
most of the current core plugins.

Change-Id: If3eb7bde4a5b8b9ca2ac0bd7327325f6c0ad620a
Closes-Bug: 1481692

commit_message:
Maintain the order of vifs between hard reboots

Ensure that the order of vifs between hard reboots
is consistent.

Closes-Bug: #1503179

Co-Authored-By: Sergey Nikitin <snikitin@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Idfdb54f18a053212c6d1d09ab8d66ed31f09ffc7

UTC/Browser time as timestamp display format

- added combobox to choose desired timestamp format
- added logic to convert server sent timestamp to browser local
- removed unused imports

commit_message:
Remove openstack_deploy from teardown.sh deletion list

This patch prevents teardown.sh script from deleting
/etc/openstack_deploy in order to let the deployer deside whether to
delete it or not.

Change-Id: Idddedfefc9ccc8bfbecdcaf20a87c1377eea1b7c
Closes-Bug: #1504561

commit_message:
libvirt: resize ploop disks with prl_disk_tool

We can't resize disks from guest OS in containers,
because they are not allowed to write directly to
block device. ploop tool can resize partition table
and internal filesystem, but only for container's
disks. Such disks must have only one partition
with ext filesystem.

prl_disk_tool can resize disks with internal filesystems
and doesn't require any special layout so it can resize
disks for virtual machines.  So it's better to use this
tool instead of ploop.

Implements blueprint virtuozzo-instance-resize-support

Change-Id: Ia0399cb3402c38ebcf6bee388025df2bb16429a6

commit_message:
Only lock in set_members on mutating operations

ipset was locking on every set_members call with an external
filesystem lock. This was expensive when lots of ports that
were a part of the same security group were on the same agent.

This patch adjusts it to check if it needs to make a change before
acquiring the semaphore.

Closes-Bug: #1502930
Change-Id: I2553ab74b7d0fbada5d573246194f83d58bd7d56

commit_message:
Add javascript jobs to openstack-health

This commit adds running javascript jobs to the openstack-health
project. The openstack-health repo contains 2 projects in 1 a REST
API on top of subunit2sql (and eventually other data sources) to query
for results history and a javascript frontend to visualize the data
returned over that rest api. Currently the repo only runs tests on
python which only covers the REST API. This commit adds testing to
the other half of the repo on the JS side.

Change-Id: Ie467df9c1f9333c04a75ca62daad82e86768f254

commit_message:
Do not rebuild revoke_tree on every token validate

Currently, the revote_tree gets rebuilt on every token validate call.
Instead rebuild only if a new entry has been added to the
revocation_event table.

Closes-Bug: #1503312
Change-Id: Id658ca8e9b7ad4022172b23bb13af7a82d04601a

commit_message:
Adding PLUMgrid plugin option to neutron setup

Taking advantage of the modularized neutron plays.
An option to use the plumgrid plumgin is added.

Implements: blueprint plumgrid-support-liberty

Change-Id: I1fa156f2a77367a23b2d652835f986e8921b2d59
Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>

commit_message:
Modularizing Neutron playbooks for master

Adding modularization for neutron setup for master.

- Core Plugin can be selected by name, and new ones added to the
  'plugins_neutron' data structure
- Agents are enabled/disabled through 'services_neutron' dict
  in roles/os_neutron/defaults/main.yml
- Upstart tasks for agentss are run based on individual enabled status
- Agent service names propagate to appropiate handler

Note: The current implementation can be further optimized when
      we move to ansible-v2. The neutron_upstart_init.yml can be
      reduced to a single task that loops on the neutron_services
      dict.

Implements: blueprint modularize-neutron-liberty

Change-Id: I655921835b9b47bc6381ac6ca0dd46d4a7bc2bbd
Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>

commit_message:
Enable role testing and make structure ansible-galaxy compatible

This patch adds the bits needed to implement automated syntax/lint
role testing. It also moves the role into the base repository so
that the role becomes fully compatible with ansible-galaxy to
improve the role's consumability.

Change-Id: Ia79cd5dedbbe50dfdf46688830a989ff0897832a

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-07 14:41:31.000000000', 'message': 'Handle images not being found

If the expected deployment kernel and ramdisk images are not found, the
deployment will fail. Technically, this is a validation error, so should
be appropriately handled via the --validation-errors-fatal cli arg.

There are reasons why such a validation should not be fatal, for
instance if the deployment images had different names than the hardcoded
ones here, etc.

Change-Id: I0bffd513b3eb79813df3971fb990950ee2bde65d
'}]
commit_message:
Handle images not being found

If the expected deployment kernel and ramdisk images are not found, the
deployment will fail. Technically, this is a validation error, so should
be appropriately handled via the --validation-errors-fatal cli arg.

There are reasons why such a validation should not be fatal, for
instance if the deployment images had different names than the hardcoded
ones here, etc.

Change-Id: I0bffd513b3eb79813df3971fb990950ee2bde65d

commit_message:
Fix the nodepool file check

The check was meant to verify two things:
 - the nodepool file exists
 - the nodepool file is not zero size

Combining them doesn't work, though, so this was never executing
as intended. This patch fixes that.

Change-Id: I7a192614afb00d11de1fd944ff20c0c89223f5c3

commit_message:
Make MySQL ignore lost+found directory in its datadir

This commit introduces optional ignore_db_dirs parameter that can be passed to
mysql::server. It is expected to be an array and is empty by default.

The backport also adds mounts fact that has been introduced in
I8a2cb4bd8d0b6070400d13e25d2310f4777b9faf.

Cherry-picked from: fb100ee828d8c0262a8343155d307fba61b5f30b
Change-Id: Ic8815b89fea41182692f9f8fafd07bbe6ca15af6
Closes-Bug: 1484552

commit_message:
Use the hostname from the Transport for GSSAPI Authentication

Previously, the AMQP 1.0 driver did not pass the proper hostname to
pyngus.  This prevented GSSAPI authentication from working properly.

Change-Id: Ibc6678e7cbae6dd5108d1650dbb8ddf837aa3648
Closes-Bug: #1503258

commit_message:
l3_odl: put request for remove_interface, not delete

remove_interface requires PUT method, not DELETE method.
Thus remove_interface results in internal server error.

Closes-Bug: #1485800
Change-Id: I9c1b6efc8343cc5256dcaa7a35c5c9771fa98479
(cherry picked from commit 6a9fe3b017fc9155db542cbe7b92b5d9268df7cd)

commit_message:
Recognize keystone version in post_test_hook

Check the environment variable set in the keystone v2 job and
modify the clouds.yaml file appropriately to use v2.

Change-Id: Iff15f915804c19811334a981abbba8c13e5eed9d

commit_message:
Move $DEST creation after logging setup

Setup the log output before calling functions like
check_path_perm_sanity that want to write out to
the error log.

Change-Id: I9815965257c399a48f8cf0f344814d954137aecb
Closes-Bug: #1500834

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-07 05:01:39.000000000', 'message': "Some minor refactoring and comment/note addition

In the internal '_run' instead of having a loop that
has various cases with quite a bit of code per case instead
have the loop call into smaller helper functions that handle
the different types of processing the loop does.

Also adds a note to the 'reset' method that explains why
the metrics keys are overwritten vs being copied/replaced
with a new copy.

Change-Id: I5ac1794d5803850120be4e67b85efe0449aa1891
"}]
commit_message:
Some minor refactoring and comment/note addition

In the internal '_run' instead of having a loop that
has various cases with quite a bit of code per case instead
have the loop call into smaller helper functions that handle
the different types of processing the loop does.

Also adds a note to the 'reset' method that explains why
the metrics keys are overwritten vs being copied/replaced
with a new copy.

Change-Id: I5ac1794d5803850120be4e67b85efe0449aa1891

commit_message:
Bump the gulp-sass version

When running with node 4.x.x the gulp-sass version required was too
old to work with the node-sass version required by the packges.json.
This commit bumps the gulp-sass version to correspond to a version
which works with node 4.

Change-Id: I7e8947449b5e86c18a008d4cdbfa3d97c98aea9a

commit_message:
Set jsonrpclib != 0.1.4

Version 0.1.4 of the jsonrpclib package came out today and is
uninstallable. Running pip wheel/install on this package results
in a stacktraced caused by a missing README.md file.

Traceback:
    Complete output from command python setup.py egg_info:
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "<string>", line 20, in <module>
      File "/tmp/pip-build-jUOSl3/jsonrpclib/setup.py", line 28, in <module>
        long_description = open("README.md").read()
    IOError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory: 'README.md'

The change is to simply skip this version.

Change-Id: I2d66bacdee433a2f7645ba8b396601c86513a218
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Removing the package scripts

There is an ongoing job for push our package repositories upstream, but
in the same time, there are the repos:

  https://github.com/midonet/networking-midonet-el
  https://github.com/midonet/networking-midonet-ubuntu

That are doing the job of these pacakage scripts. So let's keep the
sources and the packaging separate from now on.

Change-Id: I7a98aa5b8840afdc5ae12d1c7f5f270fef487a26

commit_message:
Place config and database files in home

Installation script should place config and db in home. This makes easy
to use multiuser setup. This also prevent some permissions and security
problems.

Change-Id: Ifd76215867fbf64601df201f0e58c43dacb8e5c0
Closes-Bug: 1501159

commit_message:
Fix obsolete imports in functional tests

isolated_creds was renamed to dynamic_creds in murano functional
tests. Also, update class names.

Change-Id: I3596a80925dde388dcb69a37ee4fd0343849b352
Closes-Bug: #1504508

commit_message:
test_create_router_gateway_fails fixes

- Use the existing network.  Otherwise this test fails earlier than
  intended.  (with NetworkNotFound)

- Use a dedicated exception to avoid accepting other exceptions
  like NetworkNotFound

- Move the test for L3_NAT_dbonly_mixin into a separate class.
  Skip it if the plugin does not inherit L3_NAT_dbonly_mixin.

Change-Id: Ic5d5162320bf3ff1bb8b09de3e8200ca46023b32

The root cause of this is that the option is defined in the consoleauth.__init__ which does not get imported in the consoleauth.py before we hit the line when it's needed (options get registered at import time).

It would be best to explicitly import all the needed options in all the programs in cmd/.

It is extremely difficult to test for this since tests basically import the world already.

commit_message:
load consoleauth_topic option before using it

The module wasn't correctly importing the opt, leading to a
NoSuchOptError if the option wasn't provided before calling.

Change-Id: I206af1a1532d4608bbcb5edb42d46d392b5c44ff
Closes-bug: #1503975

Removed a pile of debtcollector removals from neutron.context

The next dev cycle is up, so let's get rid of that old stuff.

Related-Bug: #1449462

(2 comments)

This looks good. 

The more I think about it, the more I think it would be best to just shutdown the process if init_host fails. Because there's nothing you can do without a proper init of the driver. So no need to 'protect' all the methods call with a decorator. We should fail early and exit.

But I can"t find a way to properly tell oslo_service.service.ProcessLauncher to not restart the process if it's gone.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-05 13:06:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Make share service understand driver init failure

Recent change [1] made share manager ignoring all driver setup errors
and continue run process. So, if driver init failed and we do not have
errors in "stats reporting" then manager/driver will report that
it is OK and scheduler will consider it alive when it is not indeed.

So, add attr 'initialized' to driver base class that will be used by
share manager to get to know is it allowed to call driver methods or
not.
Manila-share service will still run, but will be marked as 'down'.

[1] I5c4c551da9d3576ea49118ef09655d2939990cb2

Change-Id: I15d1f2aaf1d7cec6e8afb93fc32e46a877261d4e
Closes-Bug: #1502809

commit_message:
Print file sizes in indexes for on disk files

File sizes are an important piece of information in log file indexes as
they help readers pick out inappropriately sized files which may
indicate the bug can be found there. Add file sizes to the index so that
we don't lose this info when compared to mod_autoindex.

Change-Id: I248a4fc9bd5ff3fa536e30bcc981a2d5f640307c

[{'created': '2015-10-07 18:02:29.000000000', 'message': 'Dedup index entries

When we generate indexes we query disk and swift, if any files have
overlapping paths between them we were generating duplicate index
entries for the same paths. This happened because we used lists to store
the entries which allow for duplicates.

Fix this by using sets until we need to sort (sets are unsorted so we
have to have a list at that point). This will remove any duplicates and
make the index pages more correct.

commit_message:
Dedup index entries

When we generate indexes we query disk and swift, if any files have
overlapping paths between them we were generating duplicate index
entries for the same paths. This happened because we used lists to store
the entries which allow for duplicates.

Fix this by using sets until we need to sort (sets are unsorted so we
have to have a list at that point). This will remove any duplicates and
make the index pages more correct.

Change-Id: I6dfa3b30819d6633c3e483d3a386bdce3e26b572

commit_message:
iPXE: Fix assumption that ${mac} is the MAC of the NIC it's booting

The ${mac} variable not necessarily points to the MAC address of the NIC
we are booting from. This patch updates the boot.ipxe script to make it
more robust by interating over all NICs found in the machine and boot
from the first one capable of booting (the one that contains a
configuration file in the server). If no NICs are capable of booting the
script will fail just like before telling the user that the network boot
failed because we couldn't find any configuration for the present NICs.

Closes-Bug: #1504482
Change-Id: I5b8f0740fa42f611e84b66dc7f6578cffe02760a

[{'created': '2015-10-02 12:20:30.000000000', 'message': 'Adds os-win in global-requirements.txt

Hyper-V is involved in many of OpenStack components (nova, neutron,
cinder, ceilometer, etc.) and will be involved with other components
in the future.

A common library can be created in order to reduce the code duplication
between all these components (utils classes, which interacts directly
with Hyper-V through WMI), making it easier to maintain, review and
propose new changes to current and future components.

Adding os-win to the global-requirements is necessary in order to add
it as a requirement for the mentioned projects.

Partially Implements: blueprint add-os-win-library

commit_message:
Adds os-win in global-requirements.txt

Hyper-V is involved in many of OpenStack components (nova, neutron,
cinder, ceilometer, etc.) and will be involved with other components
in the future.

A common library can be created in order to reduce the code duplication
between all these components (utils classes, which interacts directly
with Hyper-V through WMI), making it easier to maintain, review and
propose new changes to current and future components.

Adding os-win to the global-requirements is necessary in order to add
it as a requirement for the mentioned projects.

Partially Implements: blueprint add-os-win-library

Change-Id: I01f19821e99659bbad123533e59a25f9a3339c94

commit_message:
Consume ConfigurableMiddleware from oslo_middleware

Middleware class in neutron/wsgi.py can be replaced with
ConfigurableMiddleware from oslo_middleware.

Remove the Debug helper class as it doesn't seem to be used
anywhere. Instead, one can use oslo_middleware.debug.Debug.

Added a note about possible implications for out-of-tree plugins
to neutron_api.rst.

Change-Id: If7360608f94625b7d0972267b763f3e7d7624fee

commit_message:
PXE: Support Extra DHCP Options for IPv6

This patch is adding a new configuration option called "ip_version" in
the "pxe" group which allow passing the IP version to the DHCP
server/Neutron port when updating the extra DHCP options for PXE
booting.

Change-Id: Ib27d977161a5278ffe4be841411404b2326401ed

commit_message:
Validate local_ip for linuxbridge-agent

When tunneling is enabled, check the availability
of the IP address in local_ip belonging to the host
interface.

Change-Id: Ic1b893d61d5efef397773cdba3b7418ef70a0417
Closes-Bug: #1483497

commit_message:
Implement a fall back URL for get-pip.py

This patch implements a fall-back URL for get-pip.py to cater for situations
where https://bootstrap.pypa.io/get-pip.py is not available (like today).

The deployer may still override the URL for the bootstrap process.

The patch also implements the fallback process in the pip_install role to
ensure that the fall back also takes place when the playbooks are run.

Change-Id: I33de85feacb633c10ed828f5d005992da6ca8a1e
(cherry picked from commit 392de6b0359445df19ae304de1d01b3d00f51661)

Maybe this is a step in the right direction but doesn't this approach still assume you've got a homogeneous set of storage nodes?

I'm wondering if perhaps discovery or some sort of mapping file (that could very easily be pre-created) would apply better here. Perhaps even tying the data back to the MAC address of a given machine (since we already have to pre-create that).

I think we could fashion a mechanism where the end user provides a file (mapping file) that we could somehow cross reference the available MAC address and then determine the desired mount point. Then perhaps we treat the parameter you are adding here more like a default value which gets used if another one isn't specified?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-24 14:10:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 8042, 'date': '2015-07-28 15:43:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@dprince what you describe is actually what we already have in place for the FencingConfig parameter. It's a workable approach in case we decide we want to allow per-node customization. If we want to go this way though, we need to keep in mind that configuring such a nested parameter is a considerably more cumbersome for the user. For FencingConfig the value usually spans 10s of lines. For fencing we didn't really have much choice (every node needs different params, practically always), but here the situation isn't so clear i think.

/me is on the fence ATM"}, {'account_id': 8042, 'date': '2015-07-28 15:46:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Provide a param to map block devices to Ceph OSDs

This change will make it possible to map block devices to be used
for the Ceph OSDs filesystem or for its journal. It defaults to
store objects in /srv/data as it was before but it allows for usage
of non-homogeneus hardware, where the name and number of block
devices is not the same across all the Ceph storage nodes, by
mapping different hashes against the local MAC address of each node.

Depends-On: I6b57febe9114888167a7b40529c068ee83232af9

Change-Id: I7f2884af3ba6613e133b9eb5a4aabf41ae0da590

commit_message:
Use sudo for pacemaker status output

The script collecting host information doesn't run as root, we need sudo
to make pacemaker status queries work. Also adding crm_verify output.

Change-Id: I5858ddf9d1d317591b4ec4e6d7633115b636709c

commit_message:
Fix MariaDB account removal race condition

The removal of default MariaDB accounts was being triggered roughly at
the same time on all controllers, causing a race condition -- multiple
nodes found an account present and attempted deletion, but then only one
succeeded with the deletion, the others failed.

HA controller deletes the accounts only on bootstrap node now, which
fixes the issue.

Change-Id: Ieacd10a6ce26da50f6a37eaa3221d866c24353fa

commit_message:
stop forcing to cinder v1

This will let openstack client use cinder v2, because apparently
shortly after switching to cinder v2, cinder v1 stopped working.

Depends-On: I6b1591800e8dcc9a672c9e9bc3287a2d344e2ce4

Change-Id: I86df44e3626cf90f74410a1a19333d66aeb0d4fb

commit_message:
make SERVICE_TIMEOUT variable

This allows us to set SERVICE_TIMEOUT per job to handle services which
might take longer to stop / start. We'll default to 30 as a reasonably
safe value.

Change-Id: I306a9ddfb957a947915eecc2d3121a15909f54d3
(cherry picked from commit a70641034af412a526611180117835e7a827acb1)

commit_message:
Fix fixed-ip schema for empty response body

Nova had bug#1356058 for response of reserve/unreserve fixed ip APIs,
where plain text ("202 Accepted The request is accepted for processing.")
was returned in response body.

It is fixed on Nova side - Ifca3081f573407808a2196e71ac1db87180db6ec
So this commit fix the response schema for those APIs.
Also rename schema as per API operations it is used for.


Change-Id: I098ee0d1fa3056f8cfb0654e2b8fd3bf75fb3e2c

commit_message:
Check for insecure cipher modes

ECB is a known insecure cipher mode and needs to be checked for.

Currently this test will only scan for pyca/cryptography's use of
ECB.  Future patches should check for PyCrypto and others.

Change-Id: I27c30cb93e814eb3b3ce6732e94a76128b5b9e81

returning 0 when the rbd_keyring was not found in the xml dump;
this change removes the -v arg so that it returns 0 (and consequently

commit_message:
Fix virsh secret cleanup script

In Ic683f2488123d8d751996a4ba17770d703f38e40 the grep command was
returning 0 when the rbd_keyring was not found in the xml dump;
this change removes the -v arg so that it returns 0 (and consequently
executes the cleanup) only if the rbd_keyring is found in the dump.

Change-Id: If8989d4f2397b5d29cfc2ce50f02e85d83002a6a

commit_message:
cli: make resource type non positional

They are no real reason to make the resource type positional
if its optional, so make it non-positional with --type/-t.

Change-Id: I53e3062c991ef1a100a82e4d3f400f11bd4ffc4a

commit_message:
provide devstack lockout with .no-devstack file.

This lets you specify that devstack should not be run by the user on
the box that you are on. Helps with running commands in the wrong
window.

Change-Id: I7aa26df1a2e02331d596bbfefb0697937787252f

The ceph locking system doesn't work as expected.
When the client loose the connection to ceph, Locks are
not released, so more code need to be added to expire
the lock when it's no more updated and/or break it when
we detect a client that hold the lock is dead.

Instead of this, this change just use tooz as meachnism system.

And a ceph driver will be added to tooz instead. Tooz have
already a tests coverage for drivers, it should be easier to
detect this kind of race.

means all gnocchi daemons must be stopped before upgrading them.

commit_message:
Removing ceph locking system

The ceph locking system doesn't work as expected.
When the client loose the connection to ceph, Locks are
not released, so more code need to be added to expire
the lock when it's no more updated and/or break it when
we detect a client that hold the lock is dead.

Instead of this, this change just use tooz as meachnism system.

And a ceph driver will be added to tooz instead. Tooz have
already a tests coverage for drivers, it should be easier to
detect this kind of race.

This change have a migration impact, changing the lock meachism
means all gnocchi daemons must be stopped before upgrading them.

Change-Id: I5662817db9cd6bbb7dc220407df42c55f862ef6b
Closes-bug: #1500646

commit_message:
Fix stack-list after failed update

When a update is being performed, the existing template is updated
incrementally as resources change. Now if update fails, template will
have mix of resources from existing and new template. Hence we need to
ensure we have the user params of both.

Closes-Bug: #1477812
Change-Id: I9e6831c58b167809e3faed519d2fb4f7c61244fc
(cherry picked from commit cb3734bf906e5c5677e499820c5d513b33aca64f)

commit_message:
Add option to deploy Docker compute role in the tripleoclient

Use the '--containerize-compute-node' flag in addition to
'--templates' flag to have your compute node deploy containers.

Depends-On: Ic8331f52b20a041803a9d74cdf0eb81266d4e03c
Change-Id: I343f56e7eb361c2f84a8fe710f03ce3e7a7737fc

commit_message:
Fixed missed translatable string inside exception

A string inside an exception was not being passed to
i18n translation so it will only show up as English if it
was ever thrown.

Here is a grep I used to make sure there were no more
exception strings that were not being passed to translations
before they were thown.
grep -r 'exception' . | grep '("' | grep -v '_'

Change-Id: I51a0d6d5b1d4053c380c8be5a0e6ac4e61985b81

commit_message:
Install and start acpid on virtual nodes

Some users may be running various nodes (including master node since
7.0) as virtual machines  acpid allows them to do graceful shutdown or
reboot without using ssh.

The commit introduces custom fact to check if ACPI is available via
procfs on machine. acpid itself is only installed and started if node is
not physical and has ACPI.

Closes-Bug: 1470172
Change-Id: I4186b4a2fbb57a0c63123377f986f888c27aa13e
Co-authored-by: Bartomiej Piotrowski <bpiotrowski@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
[Swift] Add objects context class

This patch adds new context for creating swift objects using broker
pattern.  It will create large number of containers and objects
concurrently before benchmark task like download or list objects and
delete it after task finishes.

Blueprint benchmark-scenarios-for-swift

Change-Id: I0c8623fbe56401171244542ad8188d20f8848e8c

commit_message:
Fix path of synced_folder in Vagrantfile

Vagrantfile is in dev/vagrant directory on repository,
so to reach the main directory, it should sync "../.."
path instead of "..".

Change-Id: I7d142c8239423f5de52de5602a732770bb1d7c6c
Closes-Bug: #1504426

This makes sense, but in what sense is this "Pre"? It is unordered with respect to the other software deployments, and will likely happen in parallel.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-25 07:39:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Zane: The Pre/Post refers to the ordering in overcloud-without-mergepy, so stuff that happens inside the ResourceGroup, e.g inside controller-puppet.yaml is a "Pre Configuration" step, e.g before puppet runs.

Then, inside overcloud-without-mergepy, there are a bunch of *PostDeployment resources, for example  OS::TripleO::ControllerPostDeployment which maps to controller-post-puppet.yaml, which always runs after the ResourceGroup is completed.

Thus, all the ExtraConfig interfaces which happen before puppet runs (or, more generally before the various "PostDeployment" stuff runs) were tagged as "Pre"

Maybe we can improve the naming, but it seemed like the most obvious opposite polarity to "Post" at the time :)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-25 07:43:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Arguably we would be better if anything after the ResourceGroup completed was tagged "Post", then we dropped all the "Pre" suffixes.

But, I think that ship has somewhat sailed, because we already have OS::TripleO::AllNodesExtraConfig in overcloud-without-mergepy, which would collide with any non-Pre naming adjustment here.

Overall, I think it best to stick with the "Pre" naming for now as it's consistent with the existing per-role (controller and compute) "pre configuration" interfaces, and just document where each thing happens.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-25 15:06:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-09-25 15:32:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

After careful consideration (see inline comments on next patch), I've come to the conclusion that the "Pre" part of the name "AllNodesExtraConfigPre" is perhaps the least objectionable :D

Hitherto, "AllNodes" has meant a deployment done by a separate SoftwareDeploymentGroup rather than inside the scaled unit, *not* that it applies to all types of nodes (witness "ControllerAllNodesDeployment"). So rather than appending "Pre" to make an equivalent to "AllNodesExtraConfig" inside the scaled unit, I think it would be better to drop the "AllNodes" and just call it "ExtraConfig". (Or, if you *must*, "ExtraConfigPre")

However, it appears that "ExtraConfig" already has another meaning, and it's possibly confusing to have it even appear in the name of a software deployment at all. So maybe we should just go for a completely different name, like "NodeCustomise"?'}, {'account_id': 18343, 'date': '2015-09-28 18:02:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Looks good to me.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-30 16:41:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ok, so after some discussion with zaneb, I think we reached agreement on a compromise of "OS::TripleO::NodeExtraConfig", which removes the objectionable "Pre" suffix, and the "All" thing, although it will apply to all nodes, but sticks with the "ExtraConfig" theme, as that's consistent with all other interfaces intended for external integration.

We can look at maybe renaming the other "Pre" interfaces at a later date, with aliases in the resource registry to enable backwards compatibility.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-10-01 08:13:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-01 08:13:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

"}]
commit_message:
Wire in NodeExtraConfig interface

It's become apparent that some actions are required in the pre-deploy
phase for all nodes, for example applying common hieradata overrides,
or also as a place to hook in logic which must happen for all nodes
prior to their removal on scale down (such as unregistration from
a satellite server, which currently doesn't work via the
*NodesPostDeployment for scale-down usage).

So, add a new interface that enables ExtraConfig per-node (inside the
scaled unit, vs AllNodes which is used for the cluster-wide config
outside of the ResourceGroup)

Change-Id: Ic865908e97483753e58bc18e360ebe50557ab93c

commit_message:
Mark wait_for* functions deprecated

* Mark wait_for_delete, wait_is_ready, wait_for deprecated.
* Enhance wait_for_status to handle 404 case for check resouce deletion.

Change-Id: I2ed32f1aea82b73be08439137cf97edee3827321
Implements: blueprint refactor-wait-for-functions

commit_message:
Use non-absolute url, when composing repository urls

This commit changes urls in the path of the to_url to be non-absolute,
to allow urlparse lib concatenate path and MURANO_REPO_URL with
a non-empty path component correctly.

Change-Id: I4fd2b1001e05de79b0d1813790f7c61518f1a90f
Closes-Bug: #1503593

commit_message:
swift-ring-builder can't select id=0

Currently, it is not possible to change weight of device with id=0
by swift-ring-builder cli. Instead of change the help is shown.
Example:
$ swift-ring-builder object.builder set_weight --id 0 1.00

But id=0 is generated by swift for the first device if not provided.
Also --weight, --zone and --region cause the same bug.

There is problem to detect new command format in validate_args
function if zero is as valid value for some args.

Change-Id: I4ee379c242f090d116cd2504e21d0e1904cdc2fc

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

Before that turned into a holly war I'd like to ask both of you guys two questions, one question for one guys :)

Sebastian: could you please list the negative sides of using testr which you could observe in the past.

Thomas: could you please list the advantages testr will bring. Then we will compare pros and cons and decide what to do. It will be far more productive that just calling testr either a s**t or a candy."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-09-28 17:06:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sebastian,

It's not about if testr is better or not (it is, but...). The thing is, we need Fuel to adopt the standards of OpenStack. And OpenStack is standardized around testr. So we MUST use it. It isn't like if we had a choice.

Now, one of the very good advantage of testrepository is that it is ... a test repository! Meaning that it keeps a history of failed test, and you can run only these, and fix them until they pass. "replaying" failed test is just one shell command. py.test doesn't have this feature.'}, {'account_id': 12200, 'date': '2015-09-29 07:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Use testrepository as the test runner

There are several benefits moving to testr brings
  - It reduces the diversity of tools in OpenStack
  - testrepository and related components are used in OpenStack Infra
    environment for data analisys and deeper integration
  - Reduces chances of a new dependency hell because py.test wont be
    added to global-requirements
  - Sticking to global requirements is an idea which is in the scope
    of discussions around Fuel.

In order to facilitate both running specific tests and debugging
this patch introduces dbgunit and dbgfunc tox environments that
utilize oslotest to run unit and functional tests correspondingly
and respect pdb.

Examples:

  - tox -e dbgunit v1.test_parser
  - tox -e dbgfunc v1.test_client.TestHandlers.test_env_action

Partial-bug: #1499659
Change-Id: Ia3e9c16bb21a875ceea3ea3a30c12ac8dfabc277

Make test_package_is_not_provided less strict

for equality.

commit_message:
Allign test requirements to Global Requirements

This patch allignes test requirements to Global Requirements
of the Kilo release of OpenStack both by versions ad by order.
Requirements that are not in Global Requirements list are moved
to the bottom to minimize risk of conflicts.

Partial-bug: #1499659
Change-Id: Idb6b8a459c1e35cddd359fd76c46e6b7a2d0e5da
