commit_message:
Rework pacemaker constraints from ovs and netns cleanup agents

In the current neutron-* services constraints chain, the ovs and
netns cleanup services are re-run after a neutron-server restart.
As discussed at [1] this may not be desirable leaving some neutron
services down and any tenant routers without IP.

This review introduces a second constraints chain so we now have:

neutron-server-->openvswitch-->dhcp-->l3-->metadata
and
ovs-cleanup-->netns-cleanup-->openvswitch

Instead of a single chain like

neutron-server-->ovs-cleanup-->netns-cleanup-->openvswitch-->
dhcp-->l3-->metadata

[1] https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1266910#c12

Related-Bug: 1501378
Change-Id: I4096704257aff74ff5bd37d8d01d8a776c6c6a76

commit_message:
Migrated extensions_client.py from tempest

This migrates the above files from tempest. This includes tempest commits:

 * extensions_client.py     : I8dcb70ce6ba2af59c7636c5f83157dd058fb1df3
 * test_extensions_client.py: I3ad6761651cec5e66012d08e6b63322f53286a5c
 * extensions.py            : Ica929c402a3d042ae751302384e68853eb28b405

to see the commit history for these files refer to the above Change-Ids
in the tempest repository.

Partially implements blueprint migrate-service-clients-to-tempest-lib

Change-Id: Ic658f09649ed9498fe6d3e7792a7c370772f165b

commit_message:
Network provider is not always set by tests

create_cluster() logic for network provider will be changed in
 https://review.openstack.org/#/c/232414/, so this is quick fix
to return old behaviour and get system tests working.

Change-Id: I1b3efacdd9fb945ddb3c6a5e019f192dbb09d2cc
Closes-Bug:#1504451

commit_message:
Use tempest-lib's agents_client

Now tempest-lib provides agents_client module as library and the
interface is stable. So tempest repogitory doesn't need to contain
the module.
This patch makes tempest use tempest-lib's agents_client and removes
the own module for the maintenance.

Change-Id: I610b962de89d71090d70cec7ba5db5bdf0ef75a9

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-07 06:51:20.000000000', 'message': 'Fix run-aio-build.sh for curl one-liner

The developer documentation to run an AIO build includes a curl
one-liner to run the scripts/run-aio-build.sh script. However, due to
the way it sources other scripts it will fail to execute.

This change sources those scripts in a way to allow them to be run from
curl piped to bash and also from a local git checkout.

* In run-aio-build.sh it has cd to a fresh checkout so the path can be
  assumed and hard-coded.
* In bootstrap-aio.sh and bootstrap-ansible.sh we now test the existing
  behaviour first (which will work if you executed these scripts
  directly from a git checkout) or from a scripts subdirectory of the
  currrent path (which will work if you ran the curl one-liner).

Example of documentation which includes the curl one-liner:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/openstack-ansible/developer-docs/quickstart-aio.html#running-an-aio-build-in-one-step

The curl one-liner:
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/openstack/openstack-ansible/master/scripts/run-aio-build.sh | sudo bash

commit_message:
Fix run-aio-build.sh for curl one-liner

The developer documentation to run an AIO build includes a curl
one-liner to run the scripts/run-aio-build.sh script. However, due to
the way it sources other scripts it will fail to execute.

This change sources those scripts in a way to allow them to be run from
curl piped to bash and also from a local git checkout.

* In run-aio-build.sh it has cd to a fresh checkout so the path can be
  assumed and hard-coded.
* In bootstrap-aio.sh and bootstrap-ansible.sh we now test the existing
  behaviour first (which will work if you executed these scripts
  directly from a git checkout) or from a scripts subdirectory of the
  currrent path (which will work if you ran the curl one-liner).

Example of documentation which includes the curl one-liner:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/openstack-ansible/developer-docs/quickstart-aio.html#running-an-aio-build-in-one-step

The curl one-liner:
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/openstack/openstack-ansible/master/scripts/run-aio-build.sh | sudo bash

Closes-Bug: #1504198
Change-Id: I2f8629f7cc4a1b650e8b5f6c6881168c0c5abde0

commit_message:
Add region fallback lookup

  For ceilometer, glance, cinder, nova, neutron, sahara and swift
  try to fallback region lookup on top hiera('region') key
  when creating keystone endpoints.

Change-Id: I4ac23e7e00718d02d0046ca6ff114ed26923f8d6

commit_message:
Fix cleanup of nova networks

Nova networks are tenant based resources. 
They should be deleted only once per tenant not per user

Change-Id: I9f24b5c0aff62667634a4e69219f6843edf907d4

commit_message:
[cleanup] remove vip before removing port

The VIP resource is the port with device owner: loadbalancer. We need
remove the VIP, the relationship with device owner, and then remove the
port.

Change-Id: Ied5998ed8b4760474610f2510708b7cb56c6e503
Closes-Bug: #1504388

commit_message:
Further reduced the index toctree depth

The index was still pretty unwieldy. Each spec itself offers a sidebar
with links to the specific sections, so reducing the maxdepth to 1
doesn't make navigation much more difficult. The benefit is a much
easier to skim through list of specs.

Change-Id: I27a68c32392ec05e683bf093304ed41dce6f19f2

commit_message:
add follows-standard-deprecation to Ceilometer

this adds ollows-standard-deprecation tag to Ceilometer as
Ceilometer already follows a 2 cycle deprecation period on major
features.

this is not applied to Gnocchi or Aodh as they do not have
intermediary releases.

Change-Id: I8d3cb91d66225063f6a432cc44bcf14213c8f789

commit_message:
Add openstack-ansible-security repository

This patch adds the openstack-ansible-security repository into the
openstack-ansible 'big tent'. This will be an Ansible role which
deployers optionally choose to consume.

Change-Id: Id98ece8943f52fe7acca45811412872d7f19e2a7
Depends-On: I89cd1367b13c8b85b4e76ab8281c15dbae571c01

Add the request headers and response body to the debug
logs of the token_client request. Request body is omitted because
of security reasons of not revealing passwords in the debug logs.
Also, response body has sufficient information about the type of
the token requested, therefore omitting request headers is ok.

commit_message:
Add more debug info for token_client request

Add the request headers and response body to the debug
logs of the token_client request. Request body is omitted because
of security reasons of not revealing passwords in the debug logs.
Also, response body has sufficient information about the type of
the token requested, therefore omitting request headers is ok.

Closes-Bug: #1503751
Change-Id: I830364e1df0e34398039442dc003fe46ca1db3a1

[{'created': '2015-10-08 16:30:03.000000000', 'message': 'Retry-on-deadlock added to modify package db api

On some HA database deployments such as MySQL Galera the transaction
locks are optimistic, and if the same data gets modifyed concurrently
DB server may throw a DBDeadlock error which is intended to be handled
by the caller app.

This patch adds appropriate retrying logic into the catalog db api
methods, so the operation to upload, modify or delete the package gets
retryed if the deadlock occurs due to this optimistic locking behavior.
It uses oslo_db_api.wrap_db_retry helper decorator from oslo library.

Closes-Bug: #1502589
Change-Id: I8d7b3dfb02a31eba6d55ba0bf89ac0cf05f1313d
'}]
commit_message:
Retry-on-deadlock added to modify package db api

On some HA database deployments such as MySQL Galera the transaction
locks are optimistic, and if the same data gets modifyed concurrently
DB server may throw a DBDeadlock error which is intended to be handled
by the caller app.

This patch adds appropriate retrying logic into the catalog db api
methods, so the operation to upload, modify or delete the package gets
retryed if the deadlock occurs due to this optimistic locking behavior.
It uses oslo_db_api.wrap_db_retry helper decorator from oslo library.

Closes-Bug: #1502589
Change-Id: I8d7b3dfb02a31eba6d55ba0bf89ac0cf05f1313d

commit_message:
Migrated instance_usage_audit_log_client.py from tempest

This migrates the above files from tempest. This includes tempest commits:

 * instance_usage_audit_log_client.py:      I11038a3b5e263918c150bbb304ae40a905329bef
 * test_instance_usage_audit_log_client.py: I3ad6761651cec5e66012d08e6b63322f53286a5c
 * instance_usage_audit_logs.py:            Ica929c402a3d042ae751302384e68853eb28b405

to see the commit history for these files refer to the above Change-Ids in the tempest repository

Partially implements blueprint migrate-service-clients-to-tempest-lib

commit_message:
Add heat into single controller roles

Keep flushing out our stack by adding heat into the default mix.
I look into adding a simple heat stack integration test with
another patch.

Fix length of heat auth_encryption_key to 32 chars

Depends-On: Ie8d62b449ec272f5cb7a06acdd54b3437aa57f98

Change-Id: I683aafcb060cdcb80ff7ccd025a5bd228c9b41c7

commit_message:
Move filemapper module to librarian

This commit removes 'filemapper' module from fuel-library
and replaces it to be managed via librarian.
This commit uses custom 1.1.3-mos-rc1 tag which is current
master of filemapper module as it is in fuel-library now.
There are no custom patches in this module.

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

commit_message:
Move monit module to librarian

This commit removes 'monit' module from fuel-library
and replaces it to be managed via librarian.
This commit uses custom v0.0.4-mos-rc1 tag
which is current master of monit module.
This module can be used as is from upstream master
because all our custom patches are merged in it.

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: I78821251bf3874b9c444eead23f3e295a49adb47

commit_message:
Move mongodb module to librarian

This commit removes 'mongodb' module from fuel-library
and replaces it to be managed via librarian.
This commit uses 0.10.0-mos-rc1 tag of mongodb module.
Custom patches:
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11063/
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11064/
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11065/
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11067/
All these patches will be upstreamed when this pull request
https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-mongodb/pull/194
will be finally merged.

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: Ic188f359d7fca993434fe17bc81c8d77adcd7739

commit_message:
Move openssl module to librarian

This commit removes 'openssl' module from fuel-library
and replaces it to be managed via librarian.
This commit uses custom 1.3.10-mos-rc2 tag of openssl module
because it contains 3 custom patches, which aren't
merged in upstream yet:
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11545/ - isn't in 1.3.0 version
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11546/ and
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/12263/ are part of
one upstream pull request:
https://github.com/camptocamp/puppet-openssl/pull/51
When #51 pull request will be merged in upstream
we will switch on latest upstream tag of openssl module.

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: I58c271582e6028c69e7b976ddc7f552e9e497d61

commit_message:
Check VM is reachable before data sync

Add 'wait_connection' function and make sure that target VM is
accessible before starting data copying via SSH.

Change-Id: Id87ba5df5e42924cc2669edba573a11f7b68022e
Closes-bug: #1500343

commit_message:
Fix init command

Init command was not working properly as it could not locate the
configuration sample file.
Steps taken:
- Move config-generator.tempest.conf to etc so it will be installed
with pbr.
- Update all files with new path to config-generator-tempest.conf as
needed.
- Refactor init command so if it detects we are not in a virtual
environment, try to find the global config directory /etc/tempest.
If that fails fallback to [sys.prefix]/etc/tempest.

Closes-Bug: #1491058
Closes-Bug: #1490670
Change-Id: I960bc711ff78ac2b0441ef63dff8ec4fb268fd3a

commit_message:
Increase timeout for cinder-dsvm-apache job

Make timeout similar to tempest-dsvm-full job. Current timeout value is
not enouph to execute all tests.

Change-Id: I85c3586128dc8339edfba688b76daffc144e6803

Conditionally skip some heat gate jobs

- skip dsvm jobs on docs- and unit tests-only changes
- further skip unit tests jobs on docs-only changes

commit_message:
Add jobs for the openstack-ansible-security repository

This patch adds the following jobs:

 - openstack-server-publish-jobs:
   To compile and publish the documentation for the role.

 - gate-openstack-ansible-security-docs:
   To check that the documentation compiles successfully.

 - gate-openstack-ansible-security-pep8:
   To verify that any python files in the repository are PEP8
   compliant. This is currently a non-voting check.

 - gate-openstack-ansible-security-bashate:
   To verify that any bash scripts added to the repository are
   bashate compliant. This is currently a non-voting check.

 - gate-openstack-ansible-security-ansible-lint:
   To verify syntax for all ansible tasks added to the repository.
   This is currently a non-voting check.

Depends-On: Ie0852b16f4fc0586a9e0e49dfc6202bb8bbb0290
Change-Id: I911ed0811710b8be2dab961e174db4c41895ef33

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Removed hard-coded versions from spec-files.

All hardcoded version is spec-files was reseted to neutral value,
to avoid confusion on bumping of product version
rpm-macro are used set proper version.

Change-Id: I13b6627c31aad2fbffa8375a2e7995fafa2a3b26

commit_message:
ceilometerclient: Add missing ceilometer plugin

The gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-src-python-ceilometerclient job
use the common 'tempest-dsvm-neutron-src' job-template that
doesn't setup the ceilometer plugin.

This change override this job-template for python-ceilometerclient
And add the ceilometer plugin.

Change-Id: I96de7a46aa8c2269ea76c357c8ad29ca589efecb

commit_message:
Limit the number of Ansible forks used to 10

The default MaxSessions setting for SSHD is 10. Each Ansible fork makes use of
a Session, so this patch still uses the CPU number to set the number of forks
used but limits it to 10 forks when the number of CPU's is larger.

Developer Docs and Install Guide Docs entries have been included.

Closes-Bug: #1479812
Change-Id: I9abd33e184c706796ede9963393876a8aae9837c
(cherry picked from commit fe3b328023b946413a675a0ffdbafcad353aca44)

commit_message:
Add isolated flag to pip fall back installation

To allow the fall-back mode to by-pass invalid
repo sources and pull from upstream, the
--isolated flag needs to be added to task command.

Conflicts:
>------playbooks/roles/pip_install/tasks/main.yml

Closes-Bug: #1494397
Change-Id: Ie1bc67a92718553c065e43acb00188217c8dd643
Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>
(cherry picked from commit 0d1d94afbc54ffc6fe42d30a1d9bbd52518d14e5)

commit_message:
Removing fixed settings inside the glance-cache.conf

Using same overrides for the admin_user and admin_tenant_name
as the main glance API configuration.
This fix will make sure that the glance services will use the
same set of admin settings across multiple configuration files.

Change-Id: I8009cd1b9f5548f5272d37b48ca7b43e7a0b2f86
Closes-Bug: #1503837
(cherry picked from commit a1e5b7c269f26d28cc03f8fee9c9f4c69f1e0b7f)

Thanks, Doug.  I was wondering how to do that.  I wasn't sure if it'd require a different job or not.  I suspect we'll be ready to make it voting on networking-ovn long before neutron, so I guess we'll have to define another job.

I think I'd like to wait a bit longer before adding the Neutron job.  I definitely want to be confident enough to have it voting on networking-ovn to have it running against neutron at all, because I don't want to add unreliable noise.  I also don't want to mess with it until after Liberty is out, because it'd be an unnecessary new distraction on reviews while focusing on getting the release out.

commit_message:
fix ceilometerclient gate

gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-src-python-ceilometerclient job is broken
because it does not enable ceilometer plugin and therefore
doesn't install ceilometerclient.

this creates a new job which will enable ceilometer

Change-Id: Ifa29b42a133a7f8040d72cdd468c650ec486b867

@Sridar Kandaswamy:
I was revisiting all the firewall tables ( firewall_rules, firewall_policy, firewall ) and it does seem that we should incorporate the changes in all the 3 tables.
I will update the changes, but the progress of this bug can be decided later on ( if it needs to be included in Liberty or Mitaka )

@Ann : As described above, I agree with you and Sridar. I will change all the 3 tables, but the scope of change may not be limited to firewall tables. However, as the naming convention in firewalls rules is used by the user to process certain commands, and as other modules may treat things differently. I would , for now , suggest changing only the following tables.( firewall, firewall_policy, firewall_rules)

@Henry : Once https://review.openstack.org/223935 is propagated to the master, I will commit my changes after rebasing.

If there are any issues in the above plan, then please let me know :)'}, {'account_id': 7249, 'date': '2015-09-17 13:59:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Case-Sensitivity for name column in fw table

PostgreSQL columns are case-sensitive by default, while mysql
columns are not.To maintain consistency between the firewall tables
(firewall_rules,firewall_policies,firewalls) implemented in both the
softwares,the following change has been made.This allows firewall
tables to distinguish between 'Sample' and 'sample' in both mysql and
PostgreSQL when showing/deleting information.

This patch also introduces the mitaka directory and is rebased on the
removal of  HEADS file for FWaaS.

Change-Id: Ib1cc526ba6ec1bfb1b7a639e69f8432d1ebe23fb
Closes-Bug: #1493658

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Fix incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected) as below.
  assertEqual(observed, expected) => assertEqual(expected, observed)

Target of this patch:
  manila/tests/scheduler/*
  manila/tests/volume/*
  and all others

Change-Id: I063d35c01835ed6a5c62f016274b02e29333aade
Closes-Bug: #1280522

commit_message:
Python 3 Refactoring: Replace six.iteritems() with the preferred items()

With Python3, the iteritems() method has been removed from dictionarys.
This leaves us with two options:
   1) replace with six.iteritems(dictionary)
   2) replace with dictionary.items()

The OpenStack Python 3 coders have documented their preference,
and we should follow it. Their preference is dictionary.items()

Change-Id: I2e27819404ae071bd21bfe4555e50dc8df9c65aa
Partially-Implements: blueprint barbican-py3

commit_message:
Add verbose options for Config Ref generation tool

  Add verbose option to pass autohelp.py from autohelp-wrapper
  You shoud use like
    autohelp-wrapper -v 1 update neutron
    autohelp-wrapper -v 2 update neutron

Change-Id: I5a22905ba357805faf850456e5e8f5e959c6ce2c
Closes-Bug: #1504389

tunnel is not created.

When a dhcp server is moved to new host,
1) network-hostagent binding is updated(properly i.e with new host).
2) dhcp port-hostagent binding is not updated
   ( dhcp port is still bound to old host)
If dhcp port-bound agent is different from the new dhcp agent

 notify the l2pop, and hence tunnel is not created.

As after failover, the new agent is taking care of this dhcp port,
update portbinding with the new host. This will allow neutron plugin
to notify l2pop(which will create tunnel).

Closes-Bug: 1411163

commit_message:
Update dhcp host portbinding on failover

When a dhcp server is moved to new host on failover,
tunnel is not created.

When a dhcp server is moved to new host,
1) network-hostagent binding is updated(properly i.e with new host).
2) dhcp port-hostagent binding is not updated
   ( dhcp port is still bound to old host)
If dhcp port-bound agent is different from the new dhcp agent
(which is now taking care of this dhcp port), neutron plugin won't
 notify the l2pop, and hence tunnel is not created.

As after failover, the new agent is taking care of this dhcp port,
update portbinding with the new host. This will allow neutron plugin
to notify l2pop(which will create tunnel).

Change-Id: Ib7d7dcddee005395af116ccd31a43853332ae317
Closes-bug: #1411163

commit_message:
Cleanup stale state machine during main worker thread loop

As part of the main worker thread loop, check that we still own
resources associated with the item of work.  If not, skip it and
do some cleanup.

Change-Id: If94fffe3ef3e7cc5da477a03fdfdf07d27770da8

commit_message:
mech_driver: full_sync uses unrelated context for resources

context passed to full sync is unrelated to the resource to be synced.
When necessary, the context needs to be created for the resource

Change-Id: I3d1842c2c0c95bdbaa689727a36c66e210f6273a
Related-Bug: #1371115
Closes-Bug: #1475450
(cherry picked from commit 6537676b899192b7fa96789869adce72ec8f7986)

'}, {'created': '2015-03-04 07:09:38.000000000', 'message': 'Policies based properties protection

To leverage rule based properties protection, "property_protection_file"
and "property_protection_rule_format" should be turned on in `cinder.conf`.

`property-protections-policies.conf` should be presented, typically, drop
this file in `/etc/cinder/` directory, sample configuration files are
provided with the source.

If the rule format is defined as `rule`, the rule defined in
`property-protections-policies.conf` will be parsed and appended with rules
defined in the `policy.json`.

One action(create, read, update, delete) one rule, there is no need define
multi-rules for one action since rules is recursive itself. the rule here
will be checked in the rules defined in `policy.json`, all the same with
oslo.policy verification.

Failed to pass the rule check will throw `ReservedProperty` exception, and
properties modification will fail as well.

Partially implements: bp support-modify-volume-image-metadata
Change-Id: I80ba460a0981d80e31f0943c77ca4f368a0066df

commit_message:
Policies based properties protection

To leverage rule based properties protection, "property_protection_file"
and "property_protection_rule_format" should be turned on in `cinder.conf`.

`property-protections-policies.conf` should be presented, typically, drop
this file in `/etc/cinder/` directory, sample configuration files are
provided with the source.

If the rule format is defined as `rule`, the rule defined in
`property-protections-policies.conf` will be parsed and appended with rules
defined in the `policy.json`.

One action(create, read, update, delete) one rule, there is no need define
multi-rules for one action since rules is recursive itself. The rule here
will be checked in the rules defined in `policy.json`, all the same with
oslo.policy verification.

Failing the rule check will throw `ReservedProperty` exception, and
properties modification will fail as well.

DocImpact: How to enable properties protection need to be documented.
Partially implements: bp support-modify-volume-image-metadata
Change-Id: I80ba460a0981d80e31f0943c77ca4f368a0066df

'}, {'created': '2015-03-04 07:09:38.000000000', 'message': 'Role based properties protection

To leverage role based properties protection, "property_protection_file"
and "property_protection_rule_format" should be turned on in `cinder.conf`.

`property-protections.conf` should be presented, typically, drop this file
in `/etc/cinder/` directory, sample configuration files are provided with
the source.

If the rule format is defined as `role`, the roles of the user who triggers
the modification of specific property will be compared with rule defined in
the `property-protections.conf`, if one role of user matched with the
permitted role associated with the property, rule check passed the
verification or else exception: ReservedProperty will be thrown out.

Partially implements: bp support-modify-volume-image-metadata

commit_message:
Role based properties protection

To leverage role based properties protection, "property_protection_file"
and "property_protection_rule_format" should be turned on in `cinder.conf`.

`property-protections.conf` should be presented, typically, drop this file
in `/etc/cinder/` directory, sample configuration files are provided with
the source.

If the rule format is defined as `role`, the roles of the user who triggers
the modification of specific property will be compared with rule defined in
the `property-protections.conf`, if one role of user matched with the
permitted role associated with the property, rule check passed the
verification or else exception: ReservedProperty will be thrown out.

DocImpact: How to enable properties protection need to be documented.
Partially implements: bp support-modify-volume-image-metadata
Change-Id: I58ed830a4ec080c853f3031a9842eda59bfccafe

Wait a second. So I don't think I followed this spec close enough, but seriously we need all this just to change metadata for volume image metadata? Why? We allow metadata to be set by the user because that's who owns the volume. We don't need roles when there's a one to one mapping tenant <-> volume. Also how does this property protection stuff hook into other projects besides Cinder?"}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-08-12 00:06:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

This is in the meeting agenda https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/CinderMeetings#Next_meeting'}, {'account_id': 13063, 'date': '2015-08-12 01:47:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thanks for adding this to the meeting agenda, I will be there. 

We need these stuff since image metadata may has some propeties like license key which cannot be updated even you are the owner of the volume.These properties are copied from the glance's image where they are also protected.

Most of these IMPL here is similar with what it was in the glance project, when the image properties are going to be updated/show in glance, these kind of validation is done at first.

The proerties protection is not restricted to be used for protect cinder's image metadata, but can also expose to place where this is needed."}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-08-12 02:04:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Is license key information being supported in Nova today? Are there other examples besides license key for this use case? 

Also I still have the same question of the adoption of this idea with other projects?'}, {'account_id': 13063, 'date': '2015-08-12 06:09:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Mike,
licence key is easy to understand, since changed it by an unauthorized user in Cinder may violate the billing policies for that image.

Other usecase are from what was protected in glance's image.

If the properties is immutable in the glance's image, suppose we apply the policy that 'kernel_id' or 'ramdisk_id' is immutable then we should keep it as immutable in Cinder since we can also update the bootable volume to image, does this make sense?

Not sure about this in other project beside Glance."}, {'account_id': 14624, 'date': '2015-08-14 05:27:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Introduce property utils for parsing protection files

This patch bring in the utils used to parse the property protection
files, such as property-protections.conf.

- template file for role based protections
For example, if the file listed as property_protection_file has:
[prop_a]
create = admin,spl_role

then the corresponding rule after parsing is the tuple like this,
(spl_create_prop, {"create": [admin, spl_role]})

In the list of user roles, @ means all roles and ! means no role,
! and @ are mutually exclusive.

- template file for policies based protections
For example, if the file listed as property-protections-policies.conf
has:
[prop_a]
create = cinder_creator
then the corresponding policy rule appended to the oslo policies
like this,
"prop_a:create": "rule:cinder_creator"

while cinder_creator is defined in policy.json. For example:
"cinder_creator": "role:admin or role:cinder_create_user"

This patch use role based protections template file as the start,
and policy based part will be given with `Policies based
properties protection`.

Partially implements: bp support-modify-volume-image-metadata

Change-Id: I15dbb7c647c57e04947df8cc35669ee0be9c0a24

commit_message:
tox.ini: Fix cover by giving the source directory explicitly

By default, testr assumes that the name of distribution
([metadata]name in setup.cfg) matches the name of the source directory.
However, they are different for this project.  Fix the problem by
giving the source directory explicitly via an option provided by pbr.

Closes-Bug: #1502002
Change-Id: I7a4f91d6914f187f6486ec6073d559843ef0f550

commit_message:
Revise node index assignment

This patch reworks the node index assignment logic which previously was
hard-coded upon node creation at db layer. In reality, we cannot
guarantee a NODE_CREATE action created ealier will get the index value
given that actions are executed in concurrently. This patch proposes a
work around so that next_index is preserved when creating a new node.

Change-Id: I0d2f4f26a681886079de82c18077d2db1093602f

commit_message:
Better random resource name generator

This adds a new random name generator that will make it easier to do
out-of-band cleanup of Rally-created resources. It eliminates the
ability for scenarios to specify a custom random name length and
prefix; adds a task-specific portion to the random name; and improves
configurability of random name patterns.

Subsequent commits will implement the new generator.

Implements: blueprint consistent-resource-names
Change-Id: I189474fbb185ab402e3b248421b4188b7ccde7f4

[{'created': '2015-10-09 01:58:09.000000000', 'message': 'Do not use object methods for SG callbacks

ML2 mechanism driver for MidoNet is currently used in both the Liberty
and Kilo environment, and must continue to support both cases.

In Kilo, weakref was used for storing callback methods,but that means
that the when the callback class object got garbage collected, all the
registered callback methods got lost.  This problem was fixed in
Liberty with the commit 8959032.

Until we no longer need to support Liberty mech driver working with
Kilo ML2, use module level methods for callbacks instead of object
methods.  Revert this patch when such time arrives.

Change-Id: I71b34b61624fbb40e1338eb6b267744e5d1e85fb
Closes-Bug: #1504373

commit_message:
Add references to SG callbacks to avoid GC

ML2 mechanism driver for MidoNet is currently used in both the Liberty
and Kilo environment, and must continue to support both cases.

In Kilo, weakref was used for storing callback methods where they would
get garbage collected, making all callbacks registered unavailable.
This problem was fixed in Liberty with the commit 8959032.

Until post-Liberty when we no longer need to support the mech driver
compatibility with Kilo ML2, add explicit references to the callback
methods so that they are not garbage collected.

Revert this patch when there is no need to support compatibility with
Kilo ML2.

Change-Id: I71b34b61624fbb40e1338eb6b267744e5d1e85fb
Closes-Bug: #1504373

commit_message:
Changed the way in which attrs were checked

Some memory metrics were failing because of the way
presence of attributes were checked, changed it to
a more explicit way, by using the hasattr(object, attr)
function. This is intended to fix the bug.

Change-Id: I9bf6d211679589608ca5a5bb5fd5b5a0688261ea
Closes-Bug: #1498190

commit_message:
Modified kafka max buffer size

Setting max_buffer_size to None in the kafka consumer object lets the
consumer to grow its internal buffer without limit allowing it to read messages
of any size from the kafka queue.

Change-Id: Ic47068cf1c12a9d40c6d9fe4424cf2d658955139

commit_message:
Libvirt nova: use internalURL endpoint, fix entry

Some environments may block access to the default publicURL
endpoint_type, so switching to internalURL should be more reliable.

Also, the plugin should be using a non-versioned entry point for
novaclient, see https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1493576

Change-Id: I812483294d07a75059ed166d0b2ec4251f7946f2

commit_message:
tox.ini: Fix cover by giving the source directory explicitly

By default, testr assumes that the name of distribution
([metadata]name in setup.cfg) matches the name of the source directory.
However, they are different for this project.  Fix the problem by
giving the source directory explicitly via an option provided by pbr.

Closes-Bug: #1502002
Change-Id: Iaf50fd9cb5a660dd0262211491a4f3afcb4e815c

commit_message:
Add driver framework

This abstracts all router-specific functionality into a router driver,
paving the way for the Rug managing other advanced services.

'rug-ctl router {debug, manage, update, rebuild}' commands have been
deprecated in favor of 'rug-ctl resource' equivalents, to be removed
in M.  The newer 'resource' commands are meant to address any
Rug-managed resource.  These requests are routed to the correct place
on the server-side, instead of a Neutron lookup on the client side.

Co-authored-by: Adam Gandelman <adamg@ubuntu.com>

Partially Implements: blueprint appliance-provisioning-driver
Change-Id: I1d2c68b81d28ebb0ca6ce4dcad237c4803bb96d6

commit_message:
Make deletion policy work for cluster resize action

When deleting nodes from cluster by CLUSTER_RESIZE action,
deletion policy should be triggered if it is attached to the
cluster. This patch adds this.
Also fix a small bug for MIN_SIZE and MAX_SIZE, since they can
be set to '0'.

Change-Id: I8770204b578e990fc0e82a294c1c0af6c5aaee9c

commit_message:
Import _memcache_pool normally

_memcache_pool is imported within a function so that we don't have a hard
dependency on memcache. This is a good idea but _memcache_pool doesn't
have a hard dependency on memcache either so there's no reason to
protect against this here.

Change-Id: I81418fc9fd41e40b9d508ad937d157b2f9ec44c1

commit_message:
Create Environment cache pool

We have three distinct ways that a cache pool can be created, however
only two cache pool classes with the regular _CachePool doubling up.
There's no reason for this and it's harder to read.

Create a very simple _EnvCachePool for the situation where a cache
object was passed down through environment variables.

Change-Id: I86147e887efd6ae302caa12ce996be697d36aa17

Add a description of "id" in identity API v3

In idetity API v3, the list of request parameters of "POST /v3/regions"
lacks the decriptions of "id"

Publish draft to Liberty as well

guides are generated fine.

commit_message:
Cleanup iSCSI and multipath connections better

This change back-ports a number of bug fixes and design changes that
are in the os-brick library. With these Cinder is much more capable of
correctly removing and cleaning up iSCSI multipath connections.

This is a partial cherry-pick/squash including the following changes in
os-bricks master branch:

I7a57687cac311c5e53361ccbceb1addb419f1e9f
I59bf37a932acd97cf915d086b4072b71e8214936
I1e5e9eba58a349509e80654ab3058c4ff5d00c0d
I8708db16a4b9057b09abad9f956fa5a3bb4ba54c

Change-Id: I5a23815085edad84725bf544efb2a5ef8e57bb0d
Closes-Bug: #1502534

commit_message:
Add "shared" attribute into Layer3 metering labels

Following APIs are missing "shared" attribute at request/response body.

  * POST /v2.0/metering/metering-labels
      - request/response body
  * GET  /v2.0/metering/metering-labels
      - response body
  * GET  /v2.0/metering/metering-labels/{metering-label-id}
      - response body

Change-Id: I64ef8364eb0af0de6786f63922f445057bc589ca
Closes-bug: 1503493

commit_message:
Add error response codes to create-metering-label

"Create-metering-label" should have the following error response codes:

  * badRequest (400)
  * unauthorized (401)
  * forbidden (403)

Change-Id: I29a29a7aa6c76d2cb92d7f2a9957a17629d4190a
Closes-bug: 1503524

commit_message:
Custom fixture to avoid external call in HttpCheck

Neutron was mocking urlrequest.urlopen as the original
implementation in oslo.policy was using that inside HttpCheck,
then we switched over to requests.post with change
I364ddb5f86900a3e166f4480d9f4889a68de247f
and a fresh oslo.policy version would have broken them. So
we should have a fixture to enable them to write their
tests without knowing how it is implemented.

Closes-Bug: #1503890
Change-Id: Ia482de71d3db5b89599a1d708a415364cdb468f8
